{"title_page": "Jens Bratlie", "text_new": "{{Infobox Prime Minister\n| name              = Jens Bratlie\n| image             = Jens Bratlie.jpg\n| order1            = \n| office1           = [[Prime Minister of Norway]]\n| term_start1       = 20 February 1912\n| term_end1         = 31 January 1913\n| monarch1          = [[Haakon VII of Norway|Haakon VII]]\n| governor-general1 = \n| predecessor1      = [[Wollert Konow (Prime Minister of Norway)|Wollert Konow]]\n| successor1        = [[Gunnar Knudsen]]\n| office2 = [[List of Presidents of the Storting|President of the Storting]]\n| term_start2 = 1910\n| term_end2 = 1912<br />Served with [[Magnus Halvorsen]] and [[Wollert Konow (Prime Minister of Norway)|Wollert Konow]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Edvard A. Liljedahl]]<br />[[Gunnar Knudsen]]<br />[[Carl Berner (politician)|Carl Berner]]\n| successor2 = [[J\u00f8rgen L\u00f8vland]]<br />[[S\u00f8ren Tobias \u00c5rstad]]<br />[[Gunnar Knudsen]]\n| office3 = [[Minister of Defence (Norway)|Minister of Defence]]\n| term_start3 = 20 February 1912\n| term_end3 = 31 January 1913 \n| predecessor3 = [[Karl Bull]]\n| successor3 = [[Hans Vilhelm Keilhau]]\n| primeminister3 = ''Himself''\n| office4 = [[Minister of Finance (Norway)|Minister of Finance]]\n| term_start4 = 20 February 1912\n| term_end4 = 31 January 1913\n| predecessor4 = [[Wollert Konow (Prime Minister of Norway)|Wollert Konow]]\n| successor4 = [[Gunnar Knudsen]]\n| primeminister4 = ''Himself''\n| office5 = Member of the [[Storting|Norwegian Parliament]]\n| constituency5 = [[Uranienborg, Norway|Uranienborg]]\n| term_start5     =1 January 1901\n| term_end5       = 31 December 1912\n| constituency6 = [[Uranienborg, Norway|Uranienborg]]\n| term_start6 =1 January 1916\n| term_end6 = 31 December 1918\n| birth_date       = 17 January 1856\n| birth_place      = [[Nordre Land]], [[Norway]]\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1939|9|15|1856|1|17}}\n| death_place      = [[Oslo]], [[Norway]]\n| party            = [[Conservative Party of Norway|Conservative Party]]\n| otherparty = [[National Legion (Norway)|National Legion]]\n| religion         = \n| awards = [[File:St. Olavs Orden stripe.svg|25px]][[Order of St. Olav]]<br />[[File:SWE Order of Vasa - Knight 2nd Class BAR.png|25px]] [[Order of Vasa]]<br />[[File:DNK Order of Danebrog Commander 1st Degree BAR.png|25px]] [[Order of the Dannebrog]]<br />[[File:SVE Sv\u00e4rdsorden BAR.svg|25px]] [[Order of the Sword]]\n| residence = [[Ut\u00f8ya]] \n| resting_place = [[V\u00e5r Frelsers Gravlund]]\n| spouse           =  \n| alma_mater = [[The Royal Frederick University]]\n|allegiance    = {{flag|Norway}}\n|branch        =  [[File:Norwegian army coat of arms.svg|20px]] [[Norwegian Army]]\n|serviceyears  =  1873 \u2013 1929\n|rank          =  [[File:NOR OF7.png|20px]] [[Military ranks and insignia of Norway|Major General]]\n|unit          =  \n|battles       =  \n}}\n'''Jens Kristian Meinich Bratlie''' (17 January 1856 \u2013 15 September 1939) was a [[Norway|Norwegian]] attorney and military officer. He served as an elected official representing the [[Conservative Party of Norway|Conservative Party]]. He was [[Prime Minister of Norway]] from 1912 to 1913.<ref>[http://www.regjeringen.no/en/The-Government/previous-governments/the-structure-of-the-registry/ministries-and-offices/offices/prime-minister-since-1814/jens-kristian-meinich-bratlie.html?id=463357 Jens Bratlie, Prime Minister 1912 - 1913] - [[Government.no]]</ref><ref>{{cite web\n|url=   https://www.regjeringen.no/en/the-government/previous-governments/governments/during-and-after-the-dissolution-of-the-/ministries-1905---1940/ministries-1905---1940/jens-bratlies-government-1912---1913/id507307/\n|title=    Jens Bratlie's Government. 20 February 1912 - 31 January 1913|publisher= [[Government.no]]|accessdate= May 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nJens Bratlie was born at [[Nordre Land]] in [[Oppland]], Norway.   Bratlie came from a family of leading businessmen and civil servant. He was the son of  Erik Bratlie (1814-1890) and wife Bolette Sofie Meinich (1821-1870). Following the death of his mother, he was adopted by the industrialist [[J\u00f8rgen Meinich]].<ref>{{cite web\n|url=  https://nbl.snl.no/J%C3%B8rgen_Meinich|title=    J\u00f8rgen Meinich|publisher =   Norsk biografisk leksikon \t|author=  \u00d8yvind Haugen|accessdate= May 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBratlie graduated from the Military High School in 1880 and was trained as an army officer (eventually rising to the level of Major General). He  also earned a law degree allowing him to work as a high-ranking civil servant (1886). He served several years as expedition secretary in the Department of Defense. He became Captain (1893), General Commission Commissioner (1898) and General Attorney for the Armenian Judiciary from  1906.<ref>{{cite web|url=  https://nbl.snl.no/Jens_Bratlie|title=     Jens Bratlie|publisher =  Norsk biografisk leksikon\t|author= Gunnar Christie Wasberg|accessdate= May 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBratlie held several offices such as leader of the Conservative Party (1910\u201311) and president of the Storting (1910\u201312). He was in the [[Storting]] representing Kristiania (now Oslo) 1900-12 and 1916\u201318. He served as Norwegian  [[Minister of Defence (Norway)|Minister of Defence]] and [[Minister of Auditing]] from 1912\u20131913.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=   https://www.regjeringen.no/en/the-government/previous-governments/ministries-and-offices/government-secretariats-and-ministries-s/ministries-since-1814/ministry-of-defence/id426227/|title=    Norwegian Ministry of Defence|publisher= [[Government.no]]|accessdate= May 1, 2017}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web\n|url=   https://www.regjeringen.no/en/the-government/previous-governments/ministries-and-offices/government-secretariats-and-ministries-s/ministries-since-1814/ministry-of-auditing/id426230/|title=    Norwegian Ministry of Auditing|publisher= [[Government.no]]|accessdate= May 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[1927 Norwegian parliamentary election]] he was the fourth ballot candidate for the party [[National Legion (Norway)|National Legion]], behind [[Karl Meyer (Norwegian businessman)|Karl Meyer]], [[Fr\u00f8is Fr\u00f8island]] and [[Thorvald Aadahl]].<ref>{{stort27}}</ref> In a press release, the National Legion (led by Meyer) stated that it had cherry picked \"strong\" personalities to combat the hardships in Norwegian politics.<ref>{{cite news|title=Den Nationale Legions nye valgliste for Oslo|work=[[Aftenposten Aften]]|date=23 September 1927|page=1|language=Norwegian}}</ref> Fr\u00f8island denounced the ballot in an ''[[Aftenposten]]'' piece, stating that himself, Aadahl and Bratlie was unwilling and unaware of the nomination. He stated that a vote for the National Legion would be a [[wasted vote]] in the struggle against the \"communists\". However, according to Norwegian election law the people who were listed on the ballot had no legal grounds to avoid being nominated.<ref>{{cite news|title=Den Nationale Legions liste|work=[[Aftenposten]]|date=24 September 1927|page=4|language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n\nHe served as chairman of the Conservative Party from 1911\u20131919. Following his death in 1939, his interment was at [[V\u00e5r Frelsers gravlund]].<ref>{{cite web|url=  https://lokalhistoriewiki.no/index.php/V%C3%A5r_Frelsers_gravlund|title=    V\u00e5r Frelsers gravlund|publisher= lokalhistoriewiki.no\n|accessdate= May 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Bratlie's Cabinet]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Wollert Konow (Prime Minister of Norway)|Wollert Konow]]| title=[[List of Norwegian Prime Ministers|Prime Minister of Norway]] | years=1912&ndash;1913 | after=[[Gunnar Knudsen]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{NorwegianPrimeMinisters}}\n{{Conservative Party (Norway)}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bratlie, Jens}}\n[[Category:1856 births]]\n[[Category:1939 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Nordre Land]]\n[[Category:University of Oslo alumni]]