Norway|Uranienborg]]\n| term_start5     =1 January 1901\n| term_end5       = 31 December 1912\n| constituency6 = [[Uranienborg, Norway|Uranienborg]]\n| term_start6 =1 January 1916\n| term_end6 = 31 December 1918\n| birth_date       = 17 January 1856\n| birth_place      = [[Nordre Land]], [[Norway]]\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1939|9|15|1856|1|17}}\n| death_place      = [[Oslo]], [[Norway]]\n| party            = [[Conservative Party of Norway|Conservative Party]]\n| otherparty = [[National Legion (Norway)|National Legion]]\n| religion         = \n| awards = [[File:St. Olavs Orden stripe.svg|25px]][[Order of St. Olav]]<br />[[File:SWE Order of Vasa - Knight 2nd Class BAR.png|25px]] [[Order of Vasa]]<br />[[File:DNK Order of Danebrog Commander 1st Degree BAR.png|25px]] [[Order of the Dannebrog]]<br />[[File:SVE Sv\u00e4rdsorden BAR.svg|25px]] [[Order of the Sword]]\n| residence = [[Ut\u00f8ya]] \n| resting_place = [[V\u00e5r Frelsers Gravlund]]\n| spouse           =  \n| alma_mater = [[The Royal Frederick University]]\n|allegiance    = {{flag|Norway}}\n|branch        =  [[File:Norwegian army coat of arms.svg|20px]] [[Norwegian Army]]\n|serviceyears  =  1873 \u2013 1929\n|rank          =  [[File:NOR OF7.png|20px]] [[Military ranks and insignia of Norway|Major General]]\n|unit          =  \n|battles       =  \n}}\n'''Jens Kristian Meinich Bratlie''' (17 January 1856 \u2013 15 September 1939) was a [[Norway|Norwegian]] attorney and military officer. He served as an elected official representing the [[Conservative Party of Norway|Conservative Party]]. He was [[Prime Minister of Norway]] from 1912 to 1913.<ref>[http://www.regjeringen.no/en/The-Government/previous-governments/the-structure-of-the-registry/ministries-and-offices/offices/prime-minister-since-1814/jens-kristian-meinich-bratlie.html?id=463357 Jens Bratlie, Prime Minister 1912 - 1913] - [[Government.no]]</ref><ref>{{cite web\n|url=   https://www.regjeringen.no/en/the-government/previous-governments/governments/during-and-after-the-dissolution-of-the-/ministries-1905---1940/ministries-1905---1940/jens-bratlies-government-1912---1913/id507307/\n|title=    Jens Bratlie's Government. 20 February 1912 - 31 January 1913|publisher= [[Government.no]]|accessdate= May 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nJens Bratlie was born at [[Nordre Land]] in [[Oppland]], Norway.   Bratlie came from a family of leading businessmen and civil servant. He was the son of  Erik Bratlie (1814-1890) and wife Bolette Sofie Meinich (1821-1870). Following the death of his mother, he was adopted by the industrialist [[J\u00f8rgen Meinich]].<ref>{{cite web\n|url=  https://nbl.snl.no/J%C3%B8rgen_Meinich|title=    J\u00f8rgen Meinich|publisher =   Norsk biografisk leksikon \t|author=  \u00d8yvind Haugen|accessdate= May 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBratlie graduated from the Military High School in 1880 and was trained as an army officer (eventually rising to the level of Major General). He  also earned a law degree allowing him to work as a high-ranking civil servant (1886). He served several years as expedition secretary in the Department of Defense. He became Captain (1893), General Commission Commissioner (1898) and General Attorney for the Armenian Judiciary from  1906.<ref>{{cite web|url=  https://nbl.snl.no/Jens_Bratlie|title=     Jens Bratlie|publisher =  Norsk biografisk leksikon\t|author= Gunnar Christie Wasberg|accessdate= May 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBratlie held several offices such as leader of the Conservative Party (1910\u201311) and president of the Storting (1910\u201312). He was in the [[Storting]] representing Kristiania (now Oslo) 1900-12 and 1916-18. He served as Norwegian  [[Minister of Defence (Norway)|Minister of Defence]] and [[Minister of Auditing]] from 1912-1913.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=   https://www.regjeringen.no/en/the-government/previous-governments/ministries-and-offices/government-secretariats-and-ministries-s/ministries-since-1814/ministry-of-defence/id426227/|title=    Norwegian Ministry of Defence|publisher= [[Government.no]]|accessdate= May 1, 2017}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web\n|url=   https://www.regjeringen.no/en/the-government/previous-governments/ministries-and-offices/government-secretariats-and-ministries-s/ministries-since-1814/ministry-of-auditing/id426230/|title=    Norwegian Ministry of Auditing|publisher= [[Government.no]]|accessdate= May 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[1927 Norwegian parliamentary election]] he was the fourth ballot candidate for the party [[National Legion (Norway)|National Legion]], behind [[Karl Meyer (Norwegian businessman)|Karl Meyer]], [[Fr\u00f8is Fr\u00f8island]] and [[Thorvald Aadahl]].<ref>{{stort27}}</ref> In a press release, the National Legion (led by Meyer) stated that it had cherry picked \"strong\" personalities to combat the hardships in Norwegian politics.<ref>{{cite news|title=Den Nationale Legions nye valgliste for Oslo|work=[[Aftenposten Aften]]|date=23 September 1927|page=1|language=Norwegian}}</ref> Fr\u00f8island denounced the ballot in an ''[[Aftenposten]]'' piece, stating that himself, Aadahl and Bratlie was unwilling and unaware of the nomination. He stated that a vote for the National Legion would be a [[wasted vote]] in the struggle against the \"communists\". However, according to Norwegian election law the people who were listed on the ballot had no legal grounds to avoid being nominated.<ref>{{cite news|title=Den Nationale Legions liste|work=[[Aftenposten]]|date=24 September 1927|page=4|language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n\nHe served as chairman of the Conservative Party from 1911-1919. Following his death in 1939, his interment was at [[V\u00e5r Frelsers gravlund]].<ref>{{cite web|url=  https://lokalhistoriewiki.no/index.php/V%C3%A5r_Frelsers_gravlund|title=    V\u00e5r Frelsers gravlund|publisher= lokalhistoriewiki.no\n|accessdate= May 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Bratlie's Cabinet]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Wollert Konow (Prime Minister of Norway)|Wollert Konow]]| title=[[List of Norwegian Prime Ministers|Prime Minister of Norway]] | years=1912&ndash;1913 | after=[[Gunnar Knudsen]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{NorwegianPrimeMinisters}}\n{{Conservative Party (Norway)}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bratlie, Jens}}\n[[Category:1856 births]]\n[[Category:1939 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Nordre Land]]\n[[Category:University of Oslo alumni]]\n[[Category:Fatherland League (Norway)]]\n[[Category:Norwegian Army generals]]\n[[Category:Norwegian lawyers]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Storting]]\n[[Category:Members of the Storting]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Norway]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Norway]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Conservative Party (Norway)]]\n[[Category:20th-century Norwegian politicians]]\n[[Category:Burials at V\u00e5r Frelsers gravlund]]\n\n\n{{Norway-politician-1850s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1916-18 \u2192 1916\u201318 (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jens_Bratlie"}
{"title_page": "John K. Hale", "text_new": "{{other people|John Hale}}\n'''John K. Hale''' (1807\u2013May 23, 1879) was an American lawyer and politician from [[New York (state)|New York]].\n\n==Life==\nHe was the son of John Hale and Mary (Jones) Hale. He was born in the Northern part of the [[District of Maine]], then part of [[Massachusetts]]. In 1828, he married a daughter of J. Hall, of [[Portland, Maine]].\n\nHale studied law with [[William G. Angel]].\n\nHale removed to [[Addison (town), New York|Addison]], and in 1836 to [[Hornellsville, New York|Hornellsville]], both in [[Steuben County, New York]].\n\nHe was a member of the [[New York State Assembly]] (Steuben Co., 3rd D.) in [[72nd New York State Legislature|1849]].\n\nHe was a member of the [[New York State Senate]] (26th D.) in [[79th New York State Legislature|1856]] and [[80th New York State Legislature|1857]]. He moved to [[Wyandotte County, Kansas]] in 1863 and formed a law partnership with Kansas attorney A. B. Bartlett. For several years they were the leading law firm in that city, having a large and lucrative practice,<ref name=\"Obit\">\"Senator Hale Dead\", ''The Wyandott Herald'' (June 5, 1879), p. 3.</ref> including representation of the [[Kansas Pacific Railway]].\n\nHis wife's sister Eleanor (1809\u20131877) was married to the controversial author [[John Neal (writer)|John Neal]] (1793\u20131876). In his later years, Hale had a stroke of paralysis, from which he never fully recovered. He died at the home of his daughter in [[Cortland, New York]].<ref name=\"Obit\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=E3sFAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA137 ''The New York Civil List''] compiled by Franklin Benjamin Hough (pages 137, 141, 237 and 278; Weed, Parsons and Co., 1858)\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=_pYuAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA31 ''Pen and Ink Portraits of the Senators, Assemblymen, and State Officers of New York''] by G. W. Bungay (1857; pg. 31)\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=GpoMAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA354 ''American Biographical Panorama''] by William Hunt (Albany, 1849; pg. 354f)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20051123111303/http://skyways.lib.ks.us/genweb/archives/1912/h3/hale_john_augustus.html John Augustus Hale] (his nephew) transcribed from ''Kansas: a Cyclopedia of State History etc.'' (Chicago, 1912)\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-ny-hs}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Alexander H. Stephens (Steuben County, NY)|Alexander H. Stephens]] | title = [[New York State Assembly]] <br> Steuben County, 3rd District | years = 1849 | after = James Alley}}\n{{s-par|us-ny-sen}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Andrew B. Dickinson]] | title = [[New York State Senate]] <br> 26th District | years = 1856\u20131857 | after = [[Truman Boardman]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hale, John K}}\n[[Category:1807 births]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:Members of the New York State Assembly]]\n[[Category:New York state senators]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Know Nothings]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Addison, New York]]\n[[Category:People from Wyandotte County, Kansas]]\n[[Category:19th-century American railroad executives]]\n[[Category:People from Hornellsville, New York]]\n\n\n{{NewYork-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{other people|John Hale}}\n'''John K. Hale''' (1807\u2013May 23, 1879) was an American lawyer and politician from [[New York (state)|New York]].\n\n==Life==\nHe was the son of John Hale and Mary (Jones) Hale. He was born in the Northern part of the [[District of Maine]], then part of [[Massachusetts]]. In 1828, he married a daughter of J. Hall, of [[Portland, Maine]].\n\nHale studied law with [[William G. Angel]].\n\nHale removed to [[Addison (town), New York|Addison]], and in 1836 to [[Hornellsville, New York|Hornellsville]], both in [[Steuben County, New York]].\n\nHe was a member of the [[New York State Assembly]] (Steuben Co., 3rd D.) in [[72nd New York State Legislature|1849]].\n\nHe was a member of the [[New York State Senate]] (26th D.) in [[79th New York State Legislature|1856]] and [[80th New York State Legislature|1857]]. He moved to [[Wyandotte County, Kansas]] in 1863 and formed a law partnership with Kansas attorney A. B. Bartlett. For several years they were the leading law firm in that city, having a large and lucrative practice,<ref name=\"Obit\">\"Senator Hale Dead\", ''The Wyandott Herald'' (June 5, 1879), p. 3.</ref> including representation of the [[Kansas Pacific Railway]].\n\nHis wife's sister Eleanor (1809\u20131877) was married to the controversial author [[John Neal (writer)|John Neal]] (1793\u20131876). In his later years, Hale had a stroke of paralysis, from which he never fully recovered. He died at the home of his daughter in [[Cortland, New York]].<ref name=\"Obit\"/>\n\n==Sources==\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=E3sFAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA137 ''The New York Civil List''] compiled by Franklin Benjamin Hough (pages 137, 141, 237 and 278; Weed, Parsons and Co., 1858)\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=_pYuAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA31 ''Pen and Ink Portraits of the Senators, Assemblymen, and State Officers of New York''] by G. W. Bungay (1857; pg. 31)\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=GpoMAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA354 ''American Biographical Panorama''] by William Hunt (Albany, 1849; pg. 354f)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20051123111303/http://skyways.lib.ks.us/genweb/archives/1912/h3/hale_john_augustus.html John Augustus Hale] (his nephew) transcribed from ''Kansas: a Cyclopedia of State History etc.'' (Chicago, 1912)\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-ny-hs}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Alexander H. Stephens (Steuben County, NY)|Alexander H. Stephens]] | title = [[New York State Assembly]] <br> Steuben County, 3rd District | years = 1849 | after = James Alley}}\n{{s-par|us-ny-sen}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Andrew B. Dickinson]] | title = [[New York State Senate]] <br> 26th District | years = 1856\u20131857 | after = [[Truman Boardman]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hale, John K}}\n[[Category:1807 births]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:Members of the New York State Assembly]]\n[[Category:New York state senators]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Know Nothings]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Addison, New York]]\n[[Category:People from Wyandotte County, Kansas]]\n[[Category:19th-century American railroad executives]]\n[[Category:People from Hornellsville, New York]]\n\n\n{{NewYork-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_K._Hale"}
{"title_page": "Bernhard Br\u00e6nne", "text_new": "[[File:Bernhard-Br\u00e6nne.jpg|thumb|upright|Bernhard Br\u00e6nne.]]  \n'''Bernhard Cornelius Br\u00e6nne''' (November 12, 1854 - September 7, 1927) was a [[Norway|Norwegian]] factory owner  and member of the [[Norwegian Parliament]] with the [[Conservative Party of Norway|Conservative Party]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.regjeringen.no/en/the-government/previous-governments/the-structure-of-the-registry/alphabetical-register/b.html?id=410100|title=B: Register of Persons \"Norway's Governments since 1814\"|publisher=Government.no|accessdate=2 February 2010}}</ref> \n==Background==\nBr\u00e6nne was born in [[ Trondheim]], Norway. He was the son of  Johan S\u00f8rensen Br\u00e6nne (1817\u201371) and Karen Moe (1821\u20131901). His father was the owner of a factory owner in Trondheim. The factory that he inherited from his father specialized in textile production He graduated as a chemistry engineer from Trondheim Technical College (now [[Norwegian Institute of Technology]]) from 1875. He next studied chemistry and mechanical engineering at the K\u00f6niglich-S\u00e4chsisches Polytechnikum (now [[Dresden University of Technology]]). In 1878 he took over the family business and expanded it into spinning, weaving and dry cleaning.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://snl.no/Bernhard_C._Br%C3%A6nne|title= Bernhard C. Br\u00e6nne |publisher=  Store norske leksikon|author=P\u00e5l Thonstad Sandvik|accessdate= January  1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nBr\u00e6nne was  involved in local politics in [[Trondheim]] as a member of the city council of Trondheim 1891\u20131910. He served as a member of the Norwegian [[Storting|parliament]] for several periods between and 1892 and 1918.<ref name=nbl>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Bernhard Br\u00e6nne |encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Terje|last=Bratberg|editor=Helle, Knut|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget|location=Oslo|url=http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Bernhard_Br%C3%A6nne/utdypning|language=Norwegian|accessdate=2010-05-21|editor-link=Knut Helle}}</ref> <ref name=Brissach>{{cite news|url=http://www.adressa.no/nyheter/trondheim/byens_gater/article841404.ece|title=Statsr\u00e5d for selbuvotter|last=Brissach|first=Ingrid J.|date=2007-04-10|work=[[Adresseavisen]]|language=Norwegian|accessdate=2010-05-21}}</ref>\nHe was appointed [[Minister of Labour and Social Inclusion (Norway)|Minister of Labour]] in the [[Konow's Cabinet|cabinet]] of [[Wollert Konow (Prime Minister of Norway)|Wollert Konow]] on 2 February 1910, but then replaced [[Sofus Arctander]] as [[Norwegian Ministry of Trade and Industry|Minister of Trade]] on 11 June the same year.<ref name=Konow>{{cite web|url=http://www.regjeringen.no/en/the-government/previous-governments/the-structure-of-the-registry/governments/during-and-after-the-dissolution-of-the-/ministries-1905---1940/ministries-1905---1940/wollert-konows-sb-government-1910---1912.html?id=507306|title=Wollert Konow's (S.B.) Government|publisher=Government.no|accessdate=2010-05-21}}</ref> After the accession of the [[Bratlie's Cabinet|cabinet]] of [[Jens Bratlie]] on 20 February 1912, Br\u00e6nne remained in government, again as Minister of Labour, but resigned on 23 August and was replaced by [[Nils Olaf Hovdenak]].<ref name=Bratlie>{{cite web|url=http://www.regjeringen.no/en/the-government/previous-governments/the-structure-of-the-registry/governments/during-and-after-the-dissolution-of-the-/ministries-1905---1940/ministries-1905---1940/jens-bratlies-government-1912---1913.html?id=507307|title=Jens Bratlie's Government|publisher=Government.no|accessdate=2010-05-21}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://archive.is/20160712094302/http://arkivportalen.no/side/arkiv/detaljer?arkivId=no-NTNU_arkiv000000051736 Bernhard Br\u00e6nnes private archive] existst at NTNU University Library [https://www.ntnu.no/ub/bibliotek/dora Dorabiblioteket]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Braenne, Bernhard}}\n[[Category:1854 births]]\n[[Category:1927 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Trondheim]]\n[[Category:Norwegian Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Dresden University of Technology alumni ]] \n[[Category:Members of the Storting ]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Norway]]\n[[Category: Recipients of the St. Olav's Medal]]\n\n\n{{Norway-politician-1850s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Bernhard-Br\u00e6nne.jpg|thumb|upright|Bernhard Br\u00e6nne.]]  \n'''Bernhard Cornelius Br\u00e6nne''' (November 12, 1854 - September 7, 1927) was a [[Norway|Norwegian]] factory owner  and member of the [[Norwegian Parliament]] with the [[Conservative Party of Norway|Conservative Party]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.regjeringen.no/en/the-government/previous-governments/the-structure-of-the-registry/alphabetical-register/b.html?id=410100|title=B: Register of Persons \"Norway's Governments since 1814\"|publisher=Government.no|accessdate=2 February 2010}}</ref> \n==Background==\nBr\u00e6nne was born in [[ Trondheim]], Norway. He was the son of  Johan S\u00f8rensen Br\u00e6nne (1817\u201371) and Karen Moe (1821\u20131901). His father was the owner of a factory owner in Trondheim. The factory that he inherited from his father specialized in textile production He graduated as a chemistry engineer from Trondheim Technical College (now [[Norwegian Institute of Technology]]) from 1875. He next studied chemistry and mechanical engineering at the K\u00f6niglich-S\u00e4chsisches Polytechnikum (now [[Dresden University of Technology]]). In 1878 he took over the family business and expanded it into spinning, weaving and dry cleaning.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://snl.no/Bernhard_C._Br%C3%A6nne|title= Bernhard C. Br\u00e6nne |publisher=  Store norske leksikon|author=P\u00e5l Thonstad Sandvik|accessdate= January  1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nBr\u00e6nne was  involved in local politics in [[Trondheim]] as a member of the city council of Trondheim 1891-1910. He served as a member of the Norwegian [[Storting|parliament]] for several periods between and 1892 and 1918.<ref name=nbl>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Bernhard Br\u00e6nne |encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Terje|last=Bratberg|editor=Helle, Knut|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget|location=Oslo|url=http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Bernhard_Br%C3%A6nne/utdypning|language=Norwegian|accessdate=2010-05-21|editor-link=Knut Helle}}</ref> <ref name=Brissach>{{cite news|url=http://www.adressa.no/nyheter/trondheim/byens_gater/article841404.ece|title=Statsr\u00e5d for selbuvotter|last=Brissach|first=Ingrid J.|date=2007-04-10|work=[[Adresseavisen]]|language=Norwegian|accessdate=2010-05-21}}</ref>\nHe was appointed [[Minister of Labour and Social Inclusion (Norway)|Minister of Labour]] in the [[Konow's Cabinet|cabinet]] of [[Wollert Konow (Prime Minister of Norway)|Wollert Konow]] on 2 February 1910, but then replaced [[Sofus Arctander]] as [[Norwegian Ministry of Trade and Industry|Minister of Trade]] on 11 June the same year.<ref name=Konow>{{cite web|url=http://www.regjeringen.no/en/the-government/previous-governments/the-structure-of-the-registry/governments/during-and-after-the-dissolution-of-the-/ministries-1905---1940/ministries-1905---1940/wollert-konows-sb-government-1910---1912.html?id=507306|title=Wollert Konow's (S.B.) Government|publisher=Government.no|accessdate=2010-05-21}}</ref> After the accession of the [[Bratlie's Cabinet|cabinet]] of [[Jens Bratlie]] on 20 February 1912, Br\u00e6nne remained in government, again as Minister of Labour, but resigned on 23 August and was replaced by [[Nils Olaf Hovdenak]].<ref name=Bratlie>{{cite web|url=http://www.regjeringen.no/en/the-government/previous-governments/the-structure-of-the-registry/governments/during-and-after-the-dissolution-of-the-/ministries-1905---1940/ministries-1905---1940/jens-bratlies-government-1912---1913.html?id=507307|title=Jens Bratlie's Government|publisher=Government.no|accessdate=2010-05-21}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://archive.is/20160712094302/http://arkivportalen.no/side/arkiv/detaljer?arkivId=no-NTNU_arkiv000000051736 Bernhard Br\u00e6nnes private archive] existst at NTNU University Library [https://www.ntnu.no/ub/bibliotek/dora Dorabiblioteket]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Braenne, Bernhard}}\n[[Category:1854 births]]\n[[Category:1927 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Trondheim]]\n[[Category:Norwegian Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Dresden University of Technology alumni ]] \n[[Category:Members of the Storting ]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Norway]]\n[[Category: Recipients of the St. Olav's Medal]]\n\n\n{{Norway-politician-1850s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1891-1910 \u2192 1891\u20131910", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernhard_Br%C3%A6nne"}
{"title_page": "Burton Armus", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=March 2020}}\n'''Burton Armus''' (born December 11, 1934 in [[New York City, New York]]) is an American police officer, actor, writer and television producer. Armus' Hollywood career began when, while he was still serving as an NYPD detective assigned to the 48th Squad in the Bronx, he was hired to be the [[technical advisor]] on the TV series ''[[N.Y.P.D. (TV series)|N.Y.P.D.]]'' in 1967.  He also wrote the episode \"Boys Night Out\" for that series.  Later, still a serving detective, he was picked by the late [[Telly Savalas]] to act as a technical adviser on the ''[[Kojak]]'' series.  He also acted in three of the episodes, and wrote the scripts for nine of them.  Following his retirement from the police department he moved to Los Angeles and became a successful writer and producer.  He is now retired from this second career. Director [[Richard Donner]], who directed three episodes of ''Kojak'', named a detective in his blockbuster film ''[[Superman (1978 film)|Superman]]'' after Armus.\n\n==Awards==\nIn 1994, Armus won a [[Humanitas Prize]] for 60 Minute Category (''[[NYPD Blue]]''; 1993), which was shared with [[David Milch]]. He received two [[Emmy Award]] nominations that same year, one for Outstanding Individual Achievement in Writing in a Drama Series (''NYPD Blue'') and the other for Outstanding Drama Series (''NYPD Blue''). He garnered another Emmy nomination in 1995, for Outstanding Drama Series (''NYPD Blue'').<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/bios/burton-armus|title=BURTON ARMUS|website=Television Academy|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2016/09/star-trek-gene-roddenberry-was-misogynistic-hack/|title=The Great Boor of the Galaxy|date=2016-09-09|website=National Review|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Actor===\n*''Kojak'' (Three episodes)\n*''[[Inside Moves]]''\n\n===Writer===\n*''[[Tarzan: The Epic Adventures|Tarzan - The Epic Adventures]]'' (pilot episode)\n*''[[Airwolf]]'' (Three episodes)\n*''[[Star Trek: The Next Generation]]'' (Two episodes)\n*''NYPD Blue'' (Six episodes)\n*''[[Street Hawk]]'' (One episode)\n*''[[List of Dragnet episodes (1989 series)|The New Dragnet]]'' (Eight episodes)\n*''[[Adam-12 (1990 TV series)|The New Adam-12]]'' (Eight episodes)\n*''[[The Fall Guy]]'' (Two episodes)\n*''Cassie & Company'' (Three episodes)\n*''[[Paris (1979 TV series)|Paris]]'' (One episode)\n*''[[CHiPs]]'' (One episode)\n*''[[Police Woman (TV series)|Policewoman]]'' (Two episodes)\n*''Kojak'' (Nine episodes)\n*''N.Y.P.D.'' (One episode)\n\n===Producer===\n*''The New Adam-12'' (20 episodes)\n*''The New Dragnet'' (26 episodes)\n*''Airwolf'' (1st Season)\n*''Star Trek: The Next Generation''\n*''NYPD Blue''\n*''[[Knight Rider (1982 TV series)|Knight Rider]]''\n\n===Technical Advisor===\n*''N.Y.P.D.'' (four episodes)\n*''[[Delvecchio (TV series)|Delvecchio]]'' (four episodes)\n*''Kojak'' (Ninety-five episodes)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0035953}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Armus, Burton}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American soap opera writers]]\n[[Category:American television writers]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=March 2020}}\n'''Burton Armus''' (born December 11, 1934 in [[New York City, New York]]) is an American police officer, actor, writer and television producer. Armus' Hollywood career began when, while he was still serving as an NYPD detective assigned to the 48th Squad in the Bronx, he was hired to be the [[technical advisor]] on the TV series ''[[N.Y.P.D. (TV series)|N.Y.P.D.]]'' in 1967.  He also wrote the episode \"Boys Night Out\" for that series.  Later, still a serving detective, he was picked by the late [[Telly Savalas]] to act as a technical adviser on the ''[[Kojak]]'' series.  He also acted in three of the episodes, and wrote the scripts for nine of them.  Following his retirement from the police department he moved to Los Angeles and became a successful writer and producer.  He is now retired from this second career. Director [[Richard Donner]], who directed three episodes of ''Kojak'', named a detective in his blockbuster film ''[[Superman (1978 film)|Superman]]'' after Armus.\n\n==Awards==\nIn 1994, Armus won a [[Humanitas Prize]] for 60 Minute Category (''[[NYPD Blue]]''; 1993), which was shared with [[David Milch]]. He received two [[Emmy Award]] nominations that same year, one for Outstanding Individual Achievement in Writing in a Drama Series (''NYPD Blue'') and the other for Outstanding Drama Series (''NYPD Blue''). He garnered another Emmy nomination in 1995, for Outstanding Drama Series (''NYPD Blue'').<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/bios/burton-armus|title=BURTON ARMUS|website=Television Academy|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2016/09/star-trek-gene-roddenberry-was-misogynistic-hack/|title=The Great Boor of the Galaxy|date=2016-09-09|website=National Review|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Actor===\n*''Kojak'' (Three episodes)\n*''[[Inside Moves]]''\n\n===Writer===\n*''[[Tarzan: The Epic Adventures|Tarzan - The Epic Adventures]]'' (pilot episode)\n*''[[Airwolf]]'' (Three episodes)\n*''[[Star Trek: The Next Generation]]'' (Two episodes)\n*''NYPD Blue'' (Six episodes)\n*''[[Street Hawk]]'' (One episode)\n*''[[List of Dragnet episodes (1989 series)|The New Dragnet]]'' (Eight episodes)\n*''[[Adam-12 (1990 TV series)|The New Adam-12]]'' (Eight episodes)\n*''[[The Fall Guy]]'' (Two episodes)\n*''Cassie & Company'' (Three episodes)\n*''[[Paris (1979 TV series)|Paris]]'' (One episode)\n*''[[CHiPs]]'' (One episode)\n*''[[Police Woman (TV series)|Policewoman]]'' (Two episodes)\n*''Kojak'' (Nine episodes)\n*''N.Y.P.D.'' (One episode)\n\n===Producer===\n*''