ndelof]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Tulsa, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Vigilante television series]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2019 American superhero drama television series}}\n{{Use American English|date=September 2019}} \n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Watchmen\n| image                    = [[File:Watchmen TV series logo.jpg|250px]]\n| image_alt                = \n| caption                  = \n| genre                    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Superhero fiction|Superhero]]\n* [[Utopian and dystopian fiction|Dystopia]]\n* [[Action fiction|Action]]\n* [[Drama (film and television)|Drama]]\n}}\n| creator                  = [[Damon Lindelof]]\n| based_on                 = {{based on|''[[Watchmen]]''|[[Alan Moore]]|[[Dave Gibbons]]}}<!-- Do not remove Alan Moore from this. The comic is still credited to him. The show only \"Based on characters by Dave Gibbons\", but for this infobox field, we are talking the original work-->\n| starring                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Regina King]]\n* [[Don Johnson]]\n* [[Tim Blake Nelson]]\n* [[Yahya Abdul-Mateen II]]\n* [[Andrew Howard]]\n* Jacob Ming-Trent\n* [[Tom Mison]]\n* [[Sara Vickers]]\n* Dylan Schombing\n* [[Louis Gossett Jr.]]\n* [[Jeremy Irons]]\n* [[Jean Smart]]<!--She didn't appear and wasn't credited until \"She Was Killed by Space Junk\" episode. Do NOT put her after Regina King!-->\n* [[Hong Chau]]<!--She didn't appear and wasn't credited until \"If You Don't Like My Story, Write Your Own\" episode.-->\n<!--Starring cast order is according to original broadcasting credits (the pilot episode). Do NOT rearrange cast order, per MOS:TVCAST. In addition, new starring cast members will be at the bottom of the list.-->\n}}\n| music                    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Trent Reznor]]\n* [[Atticus Ross]]\n}}\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 1<!--Only increment as a new season premieres, per the documentation of the template!-->\n| num_episodes             = 9<!--Only increment as a new episode premieres, per the documentation of the template!-->\n| list_episodes            = #Episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Damon Lindelof\n* [[Tom Spezialy]]\n* [[Nicole Kassell]]\n* [[Stephen Williams (director)|Stephen Williams]]\n* Joseph E. Iberti\n}}\n| producer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Karen Wacker \n* John Blair\n}}\n| location                 = {{Plainlist|\n* <!-- \"Nation the series was filmed in, if different from the nation of origin.\" No need to specify the state, or wikilink. -->United States\n* Wales}}\n| cinematography           = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Andrij Parekh]]\n* [[Gregory Middleton]]\n* Xavier Grobet\n* Alex Disenhof\n}}\n| editor                   = {{Plainlist|\n* David Eisenberg\n* Henk Van Eeghen\n* Anna Hauger\n}}\n| runtime                  = 52\u201367 minutes\n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n* White Rabbit\n* [[Paramount Television]]\n* [[DC Comics#DC Entertainment|DC Entertainment]]\n* {{nowrap|[[Warner Bros. Television]]}}\n}}\n| distributor              = [[Warner Bros. Television Distribution]]\n| network                  = [[HBO]]\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2019|10|20}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|2019|12|15}}\n| website                  = https://www.hbo.com/watchmen\n}}\n'''''Watchmen''''' is an American [[Superhero fiction|superhero]] [[Drama (film and television)|drama]] limited television series that continues the 1987 [[DC Comics]] series ''[[Watchmen]],'' created by [[Alan Moore]] and [[Dave Gibbons]]. The TV series was created for [[HBO]] by [[Damon Lindelof]], who also served as an executive producer and writer. Its [[ensemble cast]] includes [[Regina King]], [[Don Johnson]], [[Tim Blake Nelson]], [[Yahya Abdul-Mateen II]], [[Andrew Howard]], Jacob Ming-Trent, [[Tom Mison]], [[Sara Vickers]], Dylan Schombing, [[Louis Gossett Jr.]] and [[Jeremy Irons]], with [[Jean Smart]] and [[Hong Chau]] joining the cast in later episodes.\n\nLindelof likened the television series to a \"[[remix]]\" of the original comic series. While the series is technically a sequel, which takes place 34 years after the events of the comics within the same alternate reality, Lindelof wanted to introduce new characters and conflicts that create a new story within the ''Watchmen'' continuity, rather than creating a [[Reboot (fiction)|reboot]]. The series focuses on events surrounding racist violence in [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]], in 2019. A [[white supremacist]] group called the Seventh Kavalry has taken up arms against the [[Tulsa Police Department]] because of perceived racial injustices, causing the police to conceal their identities with masks to prevent the Seventh Kavalry from targeting them in their homes following the \"White Night\". Angela Abar (King), a detective known as Sister Night, investigates the murder of her friend and superior, Judd Crawford (Johnson), and discovers secrets regarding the situations around [[vigilantism]].\n\nThe series, originally promoted by HBO as an ongoing drama series, premiered on October 20, 2019, before concluding its nine-episode run on December 15. Lindelof left his role as showrunner after the first season, stating that he had completed his intended story. HBO subsequently confirmed there are no further plans for the show to continue without Lindelof returning in some capacity, and reclassified the work as a limited series with possible future installments.\n\n==Synopsis==\n''Watchmen'' takes place 34 years after the events of [[Watchmen|the comic series]]. Set in the comic's [[alternate history]] of the 20th century, [[Vigilantism|vigilantes]], once seen as heroes, have been outlawed due to their violent methods. In 1985, Adrian Veidt, formerly known as the vigilante [[Ozymandias (Watchmen)|Ozymandias]], created a fake attack on [[New York City]] by a [[List of Watchmen characters#Alien Monster|squid-like alien]] that resulted in millions within New York being killed, coercing nations to work together against a common threat and to avert a [[nuclear holocaust]]. Veidt's actions disgusted his former companions, with [[Rorschach (character)|Rorschach]] planning to tell the world of Veidt's misdeeds before he is vaporized by [[Doctor Manhattan]], who subsequently left the planet, unaware Rorschach had sent his journal to be published beforehand.\n\nThe show takes place in 2019 [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]]. A [[white supremacy|white supremacist]] group, the Seventh Kavalry, inspired by Rorschach's writings and masked image, wage violent war against minorities and the police that enforce special [[Reparations (transitional justice)|reparations]] for victims of racial injustice. On Christmas Eve 2016, during an event that came to be known as the \"White Night\", the Kavalry attacked the homes of 40 [[police officer]]s working for the [[Tulsa Police Department]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Why the White Night Is a Chilling Turning Point in Watchmen's Alt-History |url=https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/tv/a29612697/white-night-watchmen-hbo-show-explained/ |website=Esquire |first=Brady |last=Langmann |date=October 28, 2019 |accessdate=October 29, 2019}}</ref> Of those who survived, only two stayed with the force: Detective Angela Abar and Police Chief Judd Crawford.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.polygon.com/tv/2019/10/27/20934540/watchmen-season-1-episode-2-recap-review-explained |title=Take a close look at Watchmen episode 2 |first=Eric |last=Thurm |date=October 28, 2019 |accessdate=October 28, 2019 |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]}}</ref> As the police force was rebuilt, laws were passed that required police to not disclose their profession and to protect their identities while on the job by wearing masks, which includes allowing for costumed police officers.<ref name=\"ew deep dive\"/>\n\n==Cast and characters==\n{{main|List of Watchmen characters}}\n{{multiple image\n| align     = right\n| total_width = 500\n| perrow    = 4\n| footer    = The principal cast for ''Watchmen'' includes (top row, left to right) [[Regina King]], [[Don Johnson]], [[Jean Smart]], [[Yahya Abdul-Mateen II]], (bottom row, left to right) [[Tim Blake Nelson]], [[Hong Chau]], [[Louis Gossett Jr.]], and [[Jeremy Irons]].\n| image1    = Regina_King_by_Gage_Skidmore.jpg\n| image2    = Don_Johnson_TIFF_2019.jpg\n| image3    = Jean_Smart_by_Gage_Skidmore.jpg\n| image4    = Yahya_Abdul-Mateen_II_by_Gage_Skidmore.jpg\n| image5    = Tim Blake Nelson 2016.jpg\n| image6    = Hong Chau 2016 cropped.jpg\n| image7    = Louis Gossett Jr. (Guadalajara Film Festival) 2.jpg\n| image8    = SDCC_2015_-_Jeremy_Irons_(19524260758)_(cropped).jpg\n}}\n\n===Main===\n<!--- Cast and order per closing credits, starting from pilot episode, new cast members will be add to bottom as closing credits change, per MOS:TVCAST--->\n* [[Regina King]] as Angela Abar / Sister Night, a Tulsa Police [[detective]] who wears a [[nun]]'s [[Religious habit|habit]] and a [[Balaclava (clothing)|balaclava]]. Faithe Herman portrays a young Angela Abar.\n* [[Don Johnson]] as Judd Crawford, the [[Chief of police|chief]] of the Tulsa Police.{{efn|name=johnson|Johnson is credited with the main cast in the first and sixth episodes and is credited as a guest star in episodes two and seven.}}\n* [[Tim Blake Nelson]] as Wade Tillman / Looking Glass, a Tulsa Police detective who wears a reflective mask. Phil Labes portrays a teenage Wade.\n* [[Yahya Abdul-Mateen II]] as Calvin \"Cal\" Abar (n\u00e9 Jelani), Angela's husband who turns out to be a form of [[Doctor Manhattan|Jonathan \"Jon\" Osterman / Doctor Manhattan]]. Darrell Snedeger and Zak Rothera-Oxley portray a young Jon Osterman.<ref name=\"thr ep7\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/watchmen-season-1-episode-7-an-almost-religious-awe-explained-1258567 |title='Watchmen': Damon Lindelof Explains That \"Religious\" Reveal |first=Josh |last=Wigler |date=December 1, 2019 |accessdate=December 1, 2019 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref>\n* [[Andrew Howard]] as Red Scare, a Tulsa Police detective who wears a predominantly red outfit and speaks with a Russian accent.\n* Jacob Ming-Trent as Panda, a Tulsa Police detective who wears a full [[giant panda]] mask.\n* [[Tom Mison]] as Mr. Phillips, a series of male [[cloning|clones]] of the original Mr. Phillips originally created by Doctor Manhattan that serve as Veidt's servants.\n** Mison also portrays the Game Warden, a mysterious and powerful clone of the original Mr. Phillips who keeps Veidt in line and to serve as his archenemy.\n* [[Sara Vickers]] as Ms. Crookshanks, a series of female clones of the original Mrs. Crookshanks originally created by Doctor Manhattan that serve as Veidt's servants.\n* Dylan Schombing as Christopher \"Topher\" Abar (n\u00e9 Doyle),<ref name=\"Cast&Crew\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hbo.com/watchmen/cast-and-crew/ |title=Watchemen Cast & Crew |website=HBO |accessdate=January 10, 2020}}</ref> Angela's and Cal's adopted son whose biological parents, the Doyles, were killed on the White Night.\n* [[Louis Gossett Jr.]] as Will Reeves, Angela's grandfather, formerly known as [[List of Watchmen characters#Hooded Justice|Hooded Justice]], the first masked hero who inspired the [[List of Watchmen characters#Minutemen|Minutemen]]. [[Jovan Adepo]] portrays a young Will Reeves.\n* [[Jeremy Irons]] as [[Adrian Veidt]], a former businessman and the vigilante Ozymandias, the \"smartest man in the world\". He is now living as an aristocratic lord of a country manor that turned out to be on [[Europa (moon)|Europa]].<!--- Irons' character was confirmed as Veidt in September 2019 ---><ref>{{cite web |url=https://screenrant.com/hbo-watchmen-jeremy-irons-ozymandias-confirmed-accidentally/ |title=HBO's Watchmen Accidentally Confirms Jeremy Irons Is Playing Ozymandias |website=Screen Rant |first=Scott |last=Baird |date=September 9, 2019 |accessdate=November 2, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.polygon.com/comics/2019/10/20/20919076/hbo-watchmen-episode-1-cast-jeremy-irons-ozymandias-adrien-veidt-comic-explained |title=Ozymandias is the most important character in Watchmen |first=Susana |last=Polo |date=October 20, 2019 |accessdate=October 21, 2019 |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]}}</ref>\n* [[Jean Smart]] as [[Silk Spectre|Laurie Blake]],<ref name=\"Cast&Crew\"/> formerly the second Silk Spectre who has since become an [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] agent and member of the Anti-Vigilante Task Force.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://collider.com/watchmen-hbo-timeline-explained-rorschachs-journal/ |title=New ''Watchmen'' Site Fascinatingly Fills in the Gaps Between 1985 and 2019 |website=Collider |first=Vinnie |last=Mancuso |date=October 21, 2019 |accessdate=November 2, 2019}}</ref><!--She didn't appeared and wasn't credited until \"She Was Killed by Space Junk\" episode. Do NOT put her after Regina King!-->\n* [[Hong Chau]] as Lady Trieu, the owner of Trieu Industries, a corporation that bought out Veidt Enterprises following news of his death, and later revealed to be Veidt's daughter by artificial insemination.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/watchmen-lady-trieu-hong-chau-explained-1253706 |title='Watchmen': How a New Enigmatic Force Plans to \"Save the World\" |website=The Hollywood Reporter |first=Josh |last=Wigler |date=November 10, 2019 |accessdate=November 30, 2019}}</ref><!--She didn't appear and wasn't credited until \"If You Don't Like My Story, Write Your Own\" episode.-->\n\n===Recurring===\n<!--Reliably sourced or confirmed to make at least 4 appearances in the series.-->\n* [[James Wolk]] as Joe Keene Jr., a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] Senator and leader of the Seventh Kavalry who aims to become [[President of the United States|President]]. His father is responsible for the Keene Act banning masked vigilantism.\n* [[Frances Fisher]] as Jane Crawford, Judd's wife who is a member of the Seventh Kavalry.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/hbos-watchmen-tv-series-2019-plot-cast-reviews/ |title=HBO's Watchmen TV series: Everything you need to know |website=CNET |first=Jennifer |last=Bisset |date=October 22, 2019 |accessdate=November 2, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Jessica Camacho]] as Pirate Jenny, a member of the Tulsa police who wears a pirate-inspired outfit\n* Adelynn Spoon as Emma Abar, Angela and Cal's younger adopted daughter.\n* Lily Rose Smith as Rosie Abar, Angela and Cal's older adopted daughter.\n* Steven Norfleet as O.B. Williams, the late father of Will Reeves and great-grandfather of Angela Abar.\n* Alexis Louder as Ruth Williams, the late mother of Will Reeves and great-grandmother of Angela Abar.\n* Jolie Hoang-Rappaport as Bian, ostensibly Lady Trieu's daughter who in reality is a younger clone of Trieu's mother.\n** Elyse Dinh portrays Trieu's mother, the original Bian as an adult.\n\n===Guest starring===\n* [[Dustin Ingram]] as Agent Petey,<ref name=\"Cast&Crew\"/> an FBI agent who joins Laurie in investigating a murder in Tulsa.\n* [[Cheyenne Jackson]] as an actor portraying Hooded Justice on ''American Hero Story''.\n* [[Henry Louis Gates Jr.]] as himself, he holds the position of [[United States Secretary of the Treasury|Secretary of the Treasury]].\n* [[Jim Beaver]] as Andy, Topher's grandfather.\n* [[Lee Tergesen]] as Mister Shadow, a vigilante who is drawn out by Laurie Blake.\n* [[David Andrews (actor)|David Andrews]] as Deputy Director Max Farragut, Laurie Blake and Dale Petey's superior.\n* [[Michael Imperioli]] as himself, he appears in an advertisement for New York City<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nj.com/entertainment/2019/11/hbos-watchmen-features-nj-in-key-scene-plus-cameo-from-sopranos-actor.html |title=HBO's ''Watchmen'' features N.J. in key scene, plus cameo from 'Sopranos' actor |first=Amy |last=Kuperinsky |date=November 18, 2019 |accessdate=November 18, 2019 |work=[[NJ.com]]}}</ref>\n* Chris Whitley as an actor who portrays Captain Metropolis in ''American Hero Story''.\n* Eileen Grubba as Cynthia Bennett, Wade's ex-wife. \n* [[Paula Malcomson]] as Renee, a radiologist who is a member of the Seventh Kavalry.\n* [[Jake McDorman]] as [[List of Watchmen characters#Captain Metropolis|Nelson Gardner / Captain Metropolis]], one of the founding members of the New Minutemen.\n* [[Glenn Fleshler]] as Fred<!-- Do not link to Fred Trump, its implied to be him, but we need a full confirmation from the showrunners to make the connection -->, a racist [[shopkeeper]] who runs afoul of Will.\n* [[Danielle Deadwyler]] as June, Will's wife and Angela's grandmother who works as a reporter. Valeri Ross portrays an older June.\n* Anthony Hill as Marcus Abar, the father of Angela Abar who is killed by a suicide bomber.\n* Devyn A. Taylor as Elise Abar, the mother of Angela Abar who is killed by a suicide bomber.\n* Ted Johnson as Joe Keene Sr., the Senator who passed the Keene Act, father of Joe Keene Jr., and member of Cyclops.\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Episode table |background=#FFEF00 |overall= |title= |director= |writer= |airdate= |prodcode= |country=U.S. |viewers= |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 1\n |Title = [[It's Summer and We're Running Out of Ice]]\n |DirectedBy = [[Nicole Kassell]]\n |WrittenBy = [[Damon Lindelof]]\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|10|20}}\n |ProdCode = 101\n |Viewers = 0.799<ref name=\"1.01\">{{cite web |url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-sunday-cable-originals-network-finals-10-20-2019.html |title=Updated: ShowBuzzDaily's Top 150 Sunday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 10.20.2019 |last=Metcalf |first=Mitch |date=October 22, 2019 |work=[[Showbuzz Daily]] |accessdate=October 22, 2019}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = During Tulsa's [[Tulsa race riot|Black Wall Street massacre]] in 1921, a black child loses his parents O.B. and Ruth in the chaos and escorts an orphaned baby to safety. Ninety-eight years later, masked Officer Charlie Sutton is hospitalized after being shot by a member of the Seventh Kavalry. Chief Judd Crawford calls for retaliation to hunt down the shooter. Angela Abar hears of the shooting and hunts down a suspect under her secret persona, Sister Night. With help from another costumed police officer, Wade Tillman/Looking Glass, Angela elicits the shooter's location at a cattle ranch used by the Kavalry. Angela, Judd and other officers hunt them down, instigating a shootout that results in the deaths of all Kavalry members present, including the shooter. Sometime after the shootout, Judd runs over a spike strip while driving to the hospital to visit Sutton. Angela receives a call from someone who instructs her to find something at a countryside tree. She heads to the location, where she finds an elderly black man in a wheelchair below a hanged Judd. Meanwhile, an old lord living at an unspecified country estate writes a play called ''The Watchmaker's Son'' and celebrates an \"anniversary\" with his two servants.\n |LineColor = FFEF00\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 2\n |Title = [[Martial Feats of Comanche Horsemanship]]\n |DirectedBy = Nicole Kassell\n |WrittenBy = Damon Lindelof & Nick Cuse\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|10|27}}\n |ProdCode = 102\n |Viewers = 0.765<ref name=\"1.02\">{{cite web |url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-sunday-cable-originals-network-finals-10-27-2019.html |title=Updated: ShowBuzzDaily's Top 150 Sunday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 10.27.2019 |last=Metcalf |first=Mitch |date=October 29, 2019 |work=Showbuzz Daily |accessdate=October 29, 2019}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = In [[World War I]], O.B., a soldier in the American army, pockets a piece of German propaganda challenging their racial equality. In the present, Angela takes the elderly man she found under the tree to her hideout. He says his name is Will and claims to be her grandfather, which she later validates. The police round up several suspects from Nixonville on suspicion of Judd's lynching. Will warns Angela of Judd's duplicity, which she initially doubts. During Judd's wake however, while searching his house, she discovers a [[Ku Klux Klan]] outfit in a secret closet. She asks Will how he knew, to no avail, so she arrests him. As she places him in her car, a flying craft drops an electromagnet and takes the vehicle away with Will in it, dropping the German propaganda his father had given him. Meanwhile, the lord watches Mr. Phillips and Ms. Crookshanks perform his play: a retelling of [[Doctor Manhattan]]'s origins. Unexpectedly, the lord incinerates Phillips as part of the play and names one of his other servants\u2014apparent clones of Phillips and Crookshanks\u2014the new \"Mr. Phillips\". \n |LineColor = FFEF00\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 3\n |Title = [[She Was Killed by Space Junk]]\n |DirectedBy = [[Stephen Williams (director)|Stephen Williams]]\n |WrittenBy = Damon Lindelof & Lila Byock\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|11|3}}\n |ProdCode = 103\n |Viewers = 0.648<ref name=\"1.03\">{{cite web |url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-sunday-cable-originals-network-finals-11-3-2019.html |title=Updated: ShowBuzzDaily's Top 150 Sunday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 11.3.2019 |last=Metcalf |first=Mitch |date=November 5, 2019 |work=Showbuzz Daily |accessdate=November 5, 2019}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = After faking a bank robbery to draw out a vigilante, Agent [[Silk Spectre|Laurie Blake]] of the FBI's Anti-Vigilante Task Force is asked by both the FBI and Senator Joe Keene Jr. to investigate Judd's murder. Laurie tracks down the Tulsa police rounding up Kavalry suspects and learns about Judd's funeral, where she makes contact with Angela. A Kavalry member wearing a suicide vest attempts to seize Joe, but Laurie kills him while Angela saves the other attendees. Later, Laurie talks to Angela, discussing the wheelchair treads at Judd's lynching and Judd's secret closet; warning her not to protect Judd. That night, Laurie uses a special phone booth to tell Doctor Manhattan a \"brick joke\" while he is on Mars. As she leaves, Angela's empty car drops in front of her. She looks up, sees Mars, and laughs. Meanwhile, the lord unsuccessfully tests a protective suit with a Phillips clone. He hunts down a [[American bison|bison]] for its thicker hide, but is stopped by the \"Game Warden\", who later writes to remind him of the terms of his imprisonment. The lord responds in a letter acknowledging these terms, signing it as [[Adrian Veidt]] and goes out to hunt again in his Ozymandias outfit.\n |LineColor = FFEF00\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 4\n |Title = [[If You Don't Like My Story, Write Your Own]]\n |DirectedBy = [[Andrij Parekh]]\n |WrittenBy = Damon Lindelof & Christal Henry\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|11|10}}\n |ProdCode = 104\n |Viewers = 0.707<ref name=\"1.04\">{{cite web |url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-sunday-cable-originals-network-finals-11-10-2019.html |title=Updated: ShowBuzzDaily's Top 150 Sunday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 11.10.2019 |last=Metcalf |first=Mitch |date=November 12, 2019 |work=Showbuzz Daily |accessdate=November 12, 2019}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = Lady Trieu buys out the farmland of an Oklahoma couple just moments before an object from space crashes onto their property as to claim its ownership. Angela learns about Will's parents at the heritage center, when she hears her car crash outside and meets Laurie, finding a pill bottle inside. Later, Angela leaves the pill bottle and Judd's KKK outfit with Looking Glass, and fails to capture an unknown vigilante who witnessed her dispose of Will's wheelchair. Laurie has found Will's fingerprints in Angela's car, as well as a connection to Trieu's facility at the Millennium Clock. Trieu provides them with a list of people with access to new lightweight [[Unmanned aerial vehicle|drones]], and in Vietnamese, tells Angela that Will wonders if she got the pill bottle. That evening, Trieu talks to Will about being upfront with Angela, but with events to come to a head in a few days, he would rather she figure it out herself. Meanwhile, Veidt collects fetuses from a lake to grow new clones of Phillips and Crookshanks after killing off all of the existing ones. With their help, Veidt launches the dead bodies by [[catapult]] to test the limits of his prison.\n |LineColor = FFEF00\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 5\n |Title = [[Little Fear of Lightning]]\n |DirectedBy = Steph Green\n |WrittenBy = Damon Lindelof & [[Carly Wray]]\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|11|17}}\n |ProdCode = 105\n |Viewers = 0.752<ref name=\"1.05\">{{cite web |url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-sunday-cable-originals-network-finals-11-17-2019.html |title=Updated: ShowBuzzDaily's Top 150 Sunday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 11.17.2019 |last=Metcalf |first=Mitch |date=November 19, 2019 |work=Showbuzz Daily |accessdate=November 19, 2019}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = Wade suffers [[PTSD]] as a survivor of Veidt's 1985 squid attack. Laurie bugs Wade's desk, and learns that Angela asked him about the pills. Wade's ex-wife, Cynthia, tells him the pills are Nostalgia, which contain other people's memories. The Kavalry lure Wade to a warehouse, where they are testing a teleportation portal. Joe explains both he and Judd are Kavalry members trying to keep them in check. Joe coerces Wade's help to learn what Angela knows about Judd's death after showing him a video of Veidt, made a day before the 1985 attack and addressed to future President Redford, explaining his long-term plan; shaking Wade to his core. At the station the next day, Wade gets Angela to state that her grandfather was behind Judd's death. Laurie hears this via the audio bug and arrests Angela, but not before she ingests the pills. Wade returns home after work and Kavalry members arrive with guns. It is revealed that Veidt's prison is on [[Europa (moon)|Europa]], and arranges the frozen bodies of his servants to spell out \"SAVE ME\" so they will be visible to a passing space probe. However, he is pulled back into the prison and arrested by the Game Warden.\n |LineColor = FFEF00\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 6\n |Title = [[This Extraordinary Being]]\n |DirectedBy = Stephen Williams\n |WrittenBy = Damon Lindelof & Cord Jefferson\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|11|24}}\n |ProdCode = 106\n |Viewers = 0.620<ref name=\"1.06\">{{cite web |url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-sunday-cable-originals-network-finals-11-24-2019.html |title=Updated: ShowBuzzDaily's Top 150 Sunday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 11.24.2019 |last=Metcalf |first=Mitch |date=November 26, 2019 |work=Showbuzz Daily |accessdate=November 26, 2019}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = Laurie tries to get Angela to agree to treatment before the Nostalgia kicks in, but is too late as the latter starts to experience her grandfather's memories. In 1938, Will joins the New York Police Department, which is rife with racism. After discovering a plot called \"Cyclops\", his fellow white officers beat him and hang him from a tree, cutting him down at the last moment to warn him not to interfere in white affairs. While walking home, he dons a mask and hood to fight off men attacking a young couple. He is called a hero the next day and supported by his wife June; taking on the persona of \"Hooded Justice\". Will is invited to join the [[Minutemen (Watchmen)|Minutemen]] by Captain Metropolis and begins an affair with him while June becomes pregnant. When Will finds that \"Cyclops\" is a plan by the KKK to hypnotize black people to incite riots among themselves, Will asks for the Minutemen's help in foiling the plot, but Captain Metropolis refuses. Enraged, Will dismantles the operation on his own, killing all involved. June, shocked by Will's consuming anger, leaves him and takes their growing son \"home\" to Tulsa. In the near-present, Will uses a modified form of the hypnotic technology to make Judd hang himself. Angela wakes up at Trieu's quarters, who has been treating her for the Nostalgia.\n |LineColor = FFEF00\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 7\n |Title = [[An Almost Religious Awe]]\n |DirectedBy = [[David Semel]]\n |WrittenBy = Stacy Osei-Kuffour & Claire Kiechel\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|12|1}}\n |ProdCode = 107\n |Viewers = 0.779<ref name=\"1.07\">{{cite web |url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-sunday-cable-originals-network-finals-12-1-2019.html |title=Updated: ShowBuzzDaily's Top 150 Sunday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 12.1.2019 |last=Metcalf |first=Mitch |date=December 4, 2019 |work=Showbuzz Daily |accessdate=December 4, 2019}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = Angela continues to be treated for the Nostalgia as her memories of losing her parents and her grandmother June in Vietnam mingled with Will's. She also learns that the Manhattan phone booths supposedly connected to Mars route to Trieu's facilities before Trieu herself tells her Manhattan is actually on Earth, in Tulsa, disguised as a human. After learning of the Kavalry's plan to capture and destroy Manhattan to become like him, Trieu plans to activate the Millennium Clock within the hour to save the world. Angela breaks free, rushes home, and tells Cal she loves him as a husband \u2013 calling him by the name [[Doctor Manhattan|Jon]] \u2013 before she bashes his head in and pulls out a small disc shaped like Manhattan's symbol; his body starts to glow blue. Laurie goes to speak to Jane Crawford about her husband's death, but falls into a trap door and is taken to the Kavalry's headquarters, where Joe reveals their plan to capture Manhattan to restore white supremacy. Laurie's partner Petey tries to track down Looking Glass, finding his fallout shelter filled with dead Kavalrymen, but no sign of him. Meanwhile, Veidt is put on a year-long trial by the Game Warden, which he treats as a farce.\n |LineColor = FFEF00\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 8\n |Title = [[A God Walks into Abar]]<!-- \"Abar\" is correct: This is how it is shown on the episode's title card -->\n |DirectedBy = Nicole Kassell\n |WrittenBy = [[Jeff Jensen]] & Damon Lindelof\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|12|8}}\n |ProdCode = 108\n |Viewers = 0.822<ref name=\"1.08\">{{cite web |url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-sunday-cable-originals-network-finals-12-8-2019.html |title=Updated: ShowBuzzDaily's Top 150 Sunday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 12.8.2019 |last=Metcalf |first=Mitch |date=December 10, 2019 |work=Showbuzz Daily |accessdate=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = In Vietnam 2009, Doctor Manhattan attempts to convince Angela to have dinner with him the next night, as they will fall in love later. Angela is highly skeptical, but Manhattan, after explaining his non-linear experience with time, explains that he had been creating life on Europa since 1985, and that in 2019, he will fall in love with her just as he is about to be taken by the Seventh Kavalry. He explains how he took up the identity of Cal to blend in, and used a device created by Veidt to give him amnesia about his true identity until it was necessary for Angela to take it out. At Veidt's request, Manhattan transported him to Europa, and also visited Will to encourage him to help Angela in 2019. Angela, speaking to Manhattan in 2019, asks him to ask Will in 2009 how he knew of Judd's secrets, but realizes she gave that idea to Will just now. As the Kavalry prepare to attack, Angela goes to protect Manhattan, who sees this as the moment he fell in love with her, and helps her fend them off; knowing one last Kavalry member remained alive to use a tachyon cannon to capture him. In 2009, Angela accepts Manhattan's dinner proposal. In a post-credits scene, the Game Warden gives a captive Veidt another anniversary cake. Veidt finds a horseshoe baked inside and gleefully starts digging an escape tunnel.\n |LineColor = FFEF00\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 9\n |Title = [[See How They Fly]]\n |DirectedBy = [[Frederick E.O. Toye]]\n |WrittenBy = Nick Cuse & Damon Lindelof\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|12|15}}\n |ProdCode = 109\n |Viewers = 0.935<ref name=\"1.09\">{{cite web |url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-sunday-cable-originals-network-finals-12-15-2019.html |title=Updated: ShowBuzzDaily's Top 150 Sunday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 12.15.2019 |last=Metcalf |first=Mitch |date=December 17, 2019 |work=Showbuzz Daily |accessdate=December 17, 2019}}</ref>\n |ShortSummary = Trieu rescues her father, Veidt, from Europa as she wants him and Bian, a clone of her mother, present when she activates a machine she developed to steal Manhattan's power for herself. The Kavalry, working with the Cyclops leadership, capture Manhattan while Joe prepares to take his powers. Laurie discovers Wade is alive, disguised as a Kavalry member. Just as the Kavalry activate their system, Trieu teleports the setup to downtown Tulsa, finding Joe has dissolved into ooze, and kills the Cyclops leadership. Before Trieu kills him, Manhattan uses the distraction to teleport Veidt, Laurie, and Wade to Karnak where Veidt reworks his squid-rain system to send frozen squid to pulverize Trieu's device; killing Trieu in the process. Angela takes shelter in the theater where Will and her children are, where Will explains Manhattan had worked with him to bring about this necessary conclusion. Laurie and Wade bring Veidt to justice using the copy of the 1985 video. While cleaning up eggs from the night before, Angela recalls Manhattan's statement about transferring his powers through an organic medium. Finding one unbroken egg, Angela eats it and attempts to walk on water as she saw Manhattan do the night before.\n |LineColor = FFEF00\n}}\n}}\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nRumors of a potential ''Watchmen'' television series adaptation first came about in October 2015, with [[HBO]] in preliminary discussions with [[Zack Snyder]], director of the 2009 ''[[Watchmen (film)|Watchmen]]'' film.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Trumbore |first1=Dave |title=Exclusive: HBO Eyeing 'Watchmen' TV Series from Zack Snyder |url=http://collider.com/watchmen-tv-series-hbo-zack-snyder/ |website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]] |accessdate=June 29, 2018 |date=October 1, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151010010044/http://collider.com/watchmen-tv-series-hbo-zack-snyder/ |archive-date=October 10, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> HBO later confirmed that they were seeking to develop a ''Watchmen'' series in November 2015.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Andreeva |first1=Nellie |title=HBO Confirms \"Preliminary Discussions\" For ''Watchmen'' TV Series |url=https://deadline.com/2015/10/watchmen-tv-series-hbo-discussions-1201564953/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=June 29, 2018 |date=October 1, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107185301/https://deadline.com/2015/10/watchmen-tv-series-hbo-discussions-1201564953/ |archive-date=November 7, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Damon Lindelof by Gage Skidmore 3 (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|upright|Damon Lindelof serves as creator and writer of the TV series]]\nBy June 2017, HBO had begun negotiations with [[Damon Lindelof]], as Snyder was no longer involved with the production.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Petski |first1=Denise |title=Damon Lindelof Eyeing An Adaptation Of ''Watchmen'' For HBO |url=https://deadline.com/2017/06/damon-lindelof-adaptation-watchmen-hbo-1202117245/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=June 29, 2018 |date=June 21, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190105230459/https://deadline.com/2017/06/damon-lindelof-adaptation-watchmen-hbo-1202117245/ |archive-date=January 5, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> According to Lindelof, he had been long interested in making a ''Watchmen'' work since he read the comic as a teenager, and had been approached to write it at least twice before, but rejected the offers as they came out shortly following Snyder's film and felt he could not improve on that. In the interim, he developed the HBO series ''[[The Leftovers (TV series)|The Leftovers]]'' that ran from 2014 to 2017. ''The Leftovers'' was met with high acclaim, and led to yet another offer to write a ''Watchmen'' series, which Lindelof then accepted.<ref name=\"ew deep dive\"/>\n\nWriting for the series started on September 19, 2017.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ramos |first1=Dino-Ray |title=Damon Lindelof Teases Start Of ''Watchmen'' Series At HBO |url=https://deadline.com/2017/09/damon-lindelof-watchmen-hbo-television-series-alan-moore-dave-gibbons-1202173526/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=June 29, 2018 |date=September 19, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328165323/https://deadline.com/2017/09/damon-lindelof-watchmen-hbo-television-series-alan-moore-dave-gibbons-1202173526/ |archive-date=March 28, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The following day, HBO officially greenlit the production for a pilot and additional backup scripts as well.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Andreeva |first1=Nellie |title=''Watchmen'' HBO Adaptation From Damon Lindelof Officially A Go With Pilot & Backup Script Order |url=https://deadline.com/2017/09/watchmen-hbo-pilot-order-damon-lindelof-backup-scripts-1202174167/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=June 29, 2018 |date=September 20, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181029121824/https://deadline.com/2017/09/watchmen-hbo-pilot-order-damon-lindelof-backup-scripts-1202174167/ |archive-date=October 29, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Nicole Kassell]] was announced as the director and executive producer for the Lindelof pilot on January 30, 2018.<ref name=\"pilotcrew\">{{cite web |last1=Andreeva |first1=Nellie |title=''Watchmen'': Nicole Kassell To Direct HBO Pilot From Damon Lindelof |url=https://deadline.com/2018/01/watchmen-nicole-kassell-to-direct-hbo-pilot-damon-lindelof-1202274631/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=June 29, 2018 |date=January 30, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190328115728/https://deadline.com/2018/01/watchmen-nicole-kassell-to-direct-hbo-pilot-damon-lindelof-1202274631/ |archive-date= March 28, 2019 |url-status= live}}</ref> The pilot was filmed around June 2018 in locations around Atlanta, Georgia.<ref name=\"atlmag filming\"/>\n\nOn August 17, 2018, HBO greenlit a full season of ''Watchmen'', scheduling the premiere in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Andreeva |first1=Nellie |last2=Petski |first2=Denise |title=''Watchmen'' Is A Go: Damon Lindelof's Pilot Picked Up To Series By HBO |url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/damon-lindelof-watchmen-pilot-picked-up-series-hbo-1202447586/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=August 17, 2018 |date=August 17, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404031724/https://deadline.com/2018/08/damon-lindelof-watchmen-pilot-picked-up-series-hbo-1202447586/ |archive-date=April 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Due to the time between filming the pilot and the remaining episodes, a new production crew had been brought on board, and Kassell remained the director for the second episode to provide necessary continuity.<ref name=\"polygon kassell\">{{cite web |url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/12/8/21002009/watchmen-episode-8-director-nicole-kassell-eddies-bar-easter-eggs-doctor-manhattan-reveal |title=Watchmen director Nicole Kassell on staging the perfect Doctor Manhattan reveal |first=Tasha |last=Robinson |date=December 8, 2019 |accessdate=December 9, 2019 |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]}}</ref> The series' premiere date, October 20, 2019, was announced on September 3, 2019.<ref name=\"SeriesPremiereDate\">{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/09/watchmen-debut-date-hbo-regina-king-damon-lindelof-alan-moore-comic-1202709755/ |title=''Watchmen'' Gets Official Late October Debut Date From HBO |website=Deadline Hollywood |first=Dominic |last=Patten |date=September 3, 2019 |accessdate=September 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190903174146/https://deadline.com/2019/09/watchmen-debut-date-hbo-regina-king-damon-lindelof-alan-moore-comic-1202709755/|archive-date=September 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe show's credits identify the work as based on characters co-created by [[Dave Gibbons]], who along with [[Alan Moore]] created the ''Watchmen'' comic. Due to multiple disputes with [[DC Comics]] and the producers of previous films, Moore has asked for his name to be no longer associated with any film production of his works from that period, including for the ''Watchmen'' film.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.comicsreporter.com/index.php/alan_moore_asks_for_an_alan_smithee/ |title=Alan Moore Asks for an Alan Smithee |last=Spurgeon |first=Tom |authorlink=Tom Spurgeon |date=November 9, 2005 |work=[[The Comics Reporter]] |accessdate=January 7, 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051124004336/http://www.comicsreporter.com/index.php/alan_moore_asks_for_an_alan_smithee/ |archivedate=November 24, 2005 |url-status = live}}</ref> Lindelof had tried to reach out to Moore to get his blessing for the show but was rebuffed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/07/25/hbos-watchmen-silk-spectre-jean-smart-confirmed-alan-moore-comic-canon-robert-redford |title=HBO's Watchmen: Jean Smart Confirmed as Silk Spectre in Damon Lindelof Series |first=Laura |last=Prudom |date=July 25, 2019 |accessdate=October 22, 2019 |work=[[IGN]]}}</ref> Gibbons however was an active contributor to the show, providing illustrations in the same style as from the limited series.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/every-last-watchmen-easter-egg-and-reference-in-episode-8-of-the-hbo-show |title=Every Last Watchmen Easter Egg And Reference In Episode 8 Of The Hbo Show |first=James |last=Grebey |date=December 8, 2019 |accessdate=December 9, 2019 |work=[[Syfy]]}}</ref>\n\n===Writing===\n{{external media|image1=[https://www.instagram.com/p/BjFsj6JHEdq/ Damon Lindelof's open letter to ''Watchmen'' fans] on creating the television series, posted to Instagram on May 22, 2018}}\nLindelof stated that his vision for the series was to be a \"remix\" of the comic series. While the show is a [[sequel]] to the comic, he wanted to make a story of his own that felt part of that universe without creating a [[reboot (fiction)|reboot]], and made sure that this was apparent from the first episode.<ref name=\"ew deep dive\">{{Cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/09/18/damon-lindelof-watchmen-interview/ |title=Damon Lindelof gives his first deep-dive interview for HBO's Watchmen |first=James |last=Hibbard |date=September 18, 2019 |access-date=October 21, 2019 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]}}</ref> He affirmed this idea in an open letter to fans posted on May 22, 2018.<ref name=\"OpenLetter\">{{cite web |last1=Ramos |first1=Dino-Ray |title=Damon Lindelof's Open Letter To ''Watchmen'' Fans Says HBO Adaptation Will Be An Original Story |url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/damon-lindelof-watchmen-open-letter-hbo-series-1202396090/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |access-date=June 29, 2018 |date=May 22, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190322100936/https://deadline.com/2018/05/damon-lindelof-watchmen-open-letter-hbo-series-1202396090/ |archive-date= March 22, 2019 |url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nOne of the first challenges for Lindelof was determining what the focus of the narrative would be. He considered that at the time the original ''Watchmen'' comic was released, it reflected on the public anxiety over the ongoing [[Cold War]]. In looking for a similar anxiety for contemporary times, Lindelof determined that [[Racism|racial tensions]] posed the same type of larger picture that would work well for the ''Watchmen'' universe, since it presented both historical and present conflicts. He also felt \"to not tell a story about race in the context of a political text in 2019 almost felt borderline irresponsible\".<ref name=\"npr race\">{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/10/22/771998690/watchmen-creator-damon-lindelof-not-talking-about-race-felt-irresponsible |title='Watchmen' Creator Damon Lindelof: Not Talking About Race Felt 'Irresponsible' |first=Noel |last=King |date=October 22, 2019 |access-date=December 18, 2019 |publisher=[[NPR]]}}</ref> Establishing racism as a central theme, Lindelof assembled a purposely-diverse writing staff, with half the writers being black, and half being female, as to help provide proper perspective towards these issues.<ref name=\"vulture ep6\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/11/hooded-justice-watchmen-hbo.html |title=Who Is Hooded Justice? Watchmen Has a Stunning Answer. |first=Angela Jade |last=Bastian |date=November 24, 2019 |access-date=December 18, 2019 |work=[[Vulture (magazine)|Vulture]]}}</ref>\n\n[[File:TulsaRaceRiot-1921.png|thumb|right|The 1921 [[Tulsa race riot]] in the Greenwood district, which resulted in the deaths of over 150 black people, was a central moment to ''Watchmen''{{'}}s narrative.]]\nLindelof opted to open the pilot on the 1921 [[Tulsa race riot]], an event that he became aware of after reading ''[[The Atlantic]]'' article \"The Case for Reparations\" written by [[Ta-Nehisi Coates]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2014/06/the-case-for-reparations/361631/ |title=The Case for Reparations |first=Ta-Nehisi |last=Coates |date=June 2014 |access-date=October 21, 2019 |work=[[The Atlantic]]}}</ref> Lindelof, curious as to the riots, found there was very little information about them, and strove to learn more.<ref name=\"IGN 2019/10/21\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/10/21/watchmen-tulsa-massacre-1921-riot-oklahoma-real-history |title=Why Watchmen's Damon Lindelof Used the Tulsa Massacre of 1921 as a Backdrop |first=Scott |last=Cullera |date=October 21, 2019 |accessdate=October 21, 2019 |work=[[IGN]]}}</ref> Many aspects of the plot centers on the legacy of the graphic novel and the event.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/pop-culture/tv/watchmen-recreates-tulsa-massacre-1921-exposing-viewers-ugly-chapter-n1069426 |title='Watchmen' recreates the Tulsa massacre of 1921, exposing viewers to an ugly chapter |last=Arkin |first=Daniel |date=October 21, 2019 |work=NBC News |language=en|url-status=live|access-date=December 17, 2019}}</ref> This was around the time that he had been approached again to write for the ''Watchmen'' series, and felt the massacre and its implication for the alternate reality's present, would provide an equivalent factor that the [[Doomsday Clock]] had been for the original comic series, and used racial conflict as a central element of the series. He believed it would also help more people learn about the 1921 event, and made sure it was represented accurately, including the use of aerial attacks to destroy the [[Greenwood District, Tulsa|Greenwood district]].{{r|IGN 2019/10/21}}\n\nLindelof had conceived of Angela as the central character that everything revolves around, with the discovery that her grandfather Will, a black man, was one of the first costumed heroes, Hooded Justice, shown only in a few panels from the original comics. Hooded Justice's identity was never established in the limited series, and Lindelof's suggestion that he was a black man created a challenge for the writers. One of the first tasks the writing staff had was to determine how Will would become Hooded Justice, effectively establishing the plot to the sixth episode \"[[This Extraordinary Being]]\".<ref name=\"vulture ep6\"/> To further tie to the limited series, the writing staff only considered using the established characters that would best serve Angela's story so that she would remain the focus.<ref name=\"thr ep7\"/> To that end, they had established that characters like Doctor Manhattan, Laurie Blake, and Adrian Veidt were necessary to support Angela's discovery of her legacy. They had considered including Dan Dreiberg, the second [[Nite Owl]], as well, but Lindelof wanted to have a fair balance of old and new characters within the show, and felt that adding Dan would have tipped the balance too far away from the new characters. They did consider Dan's fate as part of the \"Peteypedia\" additional materials created by the show's writers, in which Dan remains in prison after he and Laurie were arrested for vigilantism in the past, and refusing to accept the FBI's offer to work with them as Laurie had done.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://collider.com/why-dan-dreiberg-isnt-in-watchmen-hbo/ |title=Damon Lindelof Explains Why Dan Dreiberg Wasn't in ''Watchmen'' |first=Matt |last=Goldberg |date=December 17, 2019 |access-date=December 17, 2019 |work=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]}}</ref>\n\nLindelof used his experience from his past shows to plot out the season prior to writing, stating \"What I've learned over time is you need to know the answers to the mysteries...If you don't know those, you're lost. Every time you come to an intersection, you won't know whether to turn left or right.\"<ref name=\"variety behind\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/watchmen-damon-lindelof-behind-the-scenes-1203436108/ |title=How ''Watchmen'' Pulled Off One of the Best TV Seasons of the Decade |first=Adam |last=Vary |date=December 13, 2019 |access-date=December 13, 2019 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref> The writers had established some of the season's key mysteries in writing for the pilot, such as Hooded Justice being Will Reeves and Cal being Doctor Manhattan, but how these were to be revealed to the characters in the show and the audience came later in the writing process.<ref name=\"variety behind\"/> Ten episodes were originally planned for the first season. After completing the sixth episode, \"[[This Extraordinary Being]]\", Lindelof felt the story was closer to its ending rather than as a midpoint, and that if they continued for four additional episodes, one of them would have been [[filler (media)|filler]], and instead opted to conclude the story with three episodes. The omitted episode would have likely covered more of Lady Trieu's backstory, according to Lindelof, though it would not have been exclusively devoted to that topic. Instead, some of this material was covered in conversations within the seventh episode \"[[An Almost Religious Awe]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://collider.com/why-watchmen-was-9-episodes-instead-of-10/ |title=Damon Lindelof Explains Why ''Watchmen'' Was Shortened to 9 Episodes Instead of the Original 10 |first=Adam |last=Chitwood |date=December 17, 2019 |access-date=December 17, 2019 |work=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]}}</ref>\n\nA show-within-the-show, ''American Hero Story'', was used to tell the purported backstory of Hooded Justice. Writer Cord Jefferson said ''American Hero Story'' was meant to be the opposite to what they were creating for the actual show, a \"cheesy\" production that perpetuated the in-universe myth of Hooded Justice being a white man.<ref name=\"vulture ep6\"/> Lindelof said the show was designed to be comparable to [[Ryan Murphy (writer)|Ryan Murphy]]'s series ''[[American Horror Story]]'' and ''[[American Crime Story]]'', and had even considered bringing in Murphy to play himself as the producer of ''American Hero Story''. He opted against this, but still treated ''American Hero Story'' like a Murphy work, and taking its producer to be somewhat secretive and seclusive, like Murphy.<ref name=\"ahs\"/> Some media critics took the ''American Hero Story'' segments to be a parody of [[Zack Snyder]]'s [[Watchmen (film)|2009 live-action adaption of ''Watchmen'']], a work generally panned by fans of the comic, but Lindelof and Kassell asserted this was not their intent. Kassell said \"I fully admire [Snyder] as a filmmaker so to hear that it could even be used as a negative comment feels terrible. What I was wanting to do with those (American Hero Story scenes) is like, 'This is the version we could make,' and we are very concretely not making that version. We're grounding our story in a much more real kind of naturalism.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cinemablend.com/television/2486877/no-hbos-watchmen-wasnt-trolling-zack-snyders-movie-producers-address-theory |title=No, HBO's Watchmen Wasn't Trolling Zack Snyder's Movie: Producers Address Theory |first=Nick |last=Venable |date=December 17, 2019 |accessdate=December 19, 2019 |work=Cinema Blend}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nOn May 23, 2018, it was announced that [[Regina King]], [[Don Johnson]], [[Tim Blake Nelson]], [[Louis Gossett Jr.]], [[Adelaide Clemens]], and [[Andrew Howard]] had joined the cast of the pilot. At least one of the actors was expected to have been cast in a potentially recurring role.<ref name=\"Cast1\">{{cite web |last1=Andreeva |first1=Nellie |last2=Petski |first2=Denise |title=''Watchmen'': Regina King, Don Johnson, Louis Gossett Jr., Andrew Howard Among Six Cast In Damon Lindelof's HBO Pilot |url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/watchmen-regina-king-don-johnson-louis-gossett-jr-andrew-howard-among-six-cast-in-damon-lindelofs-hbo-pilot-1202396744/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=June 29, 2018 |date=May 23, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181205092535/https://deadline.com/2018/05/watchmen-regina-king-don-johnson-louis-gossett-jr-andrew-howard-among-six-cast-in-damon-lindelofs-hbo-pilot-1202396744/ |archive-date= December 5, 2018 |url-status= live}}</ref> In June 2018, it was reported that [[Jeremy Irons]], [[Tom Mison]], [[Frances Fisher]], Jacob Ming-Trent, [[Yahya Abdul-Mateen II]], and [[Sara Vickers]] had been cast in the pilot.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Andreeva |first1=Nellie |title=''Watchmen'': Jeremy Irons To Star In Damon Lindelof's HBO Pilot |url=https://deadline.com/2018/06/watchmen-jeremy-irons-cast-damon-lindelof-hbo-pilot-1202417623/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=June 29, 2018 |date=June 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190105235259/https://deadline.com/2018/06/watchmen-jeremy-irons-cast-damon-lindelof-hbo-pilot-1202417623/ |archive-date=January 5, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Petski |first1=Denise |title=''Watchmen'': Tom Mison, Frances Fisher & Jacob Ming-Trent Cast In Damon Lindelof's HBO Pilot |url=https://deadline.com/2018/06/watchmen-tom-mison-frances-fisher-jacob-ming-trent-cast-damon-lindelof-hbo-pilot-1202418940/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=June 29, 2018 |date=June 28, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180818052243/https://deadline.com/2018/06/watchmen-tom-mison-frances-fisher-jacob-ming-trent-cast-damon-lindelof-hbo-pilot-1202418940/ |archive-date=August 18, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Petski |first1=Denise |title=''Watchmen'': Yahya Abdul-Mateen II & Sara Vickers Cast In Damon Lindelof's HBO Pilot |url=https://deadline.com/2018/06/watchmen-yahya-abdul-mateen-ii-sara-vickers-cast-damon-lindelofs-hbo-pilot-1202419601/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=June 29, 2018 |date=June 29, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190322030926/https://deadline.com/2018/06/watchmen-yahya-abdul-mateen-ii-sara-vickers-cast-damon-lindelofs-hbo-pilot-1202419601/ |archive-date=March 22, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> On August 7, 2018, it was announced that Dylan Schombing, Adelynn Spoon, and Lily Rose Smith had joined the pilot's cast.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Petski |first1=Denise |title=''Watchmen'': Dylan Schombing, Adelynn Spoon & Lily Rose Smith Join Damon Lindelof's HBO Pilot |url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/watchmen-dylan-schombing-adelynn-spoon-lily-rose-smith-damon-lindelof-hbo-pilot-1202442037/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=August 7, 2018 |date=August 7, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180825184224/https://deadline.com/2018/08/watchmen-dylan-schombing-adelynn-spoon-lily-rose-smith-damon-lindelof-hbo-pilot-1202442037/ |archive-date= August 25, 2018 |url-status= live}}</ref> In November 2018, it was reported that [[Jean Smart]] had been cast in a starring role and that [[James Wolk]] would appear in a recurring capacity. Additionally, it was confirmed that Irons would portray [[Ozymandias (Watchmen)|Adrian Veidt / Ozymandias]], that Nelson would portray a newly-devised character named Looking Glass,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Andreeva |first1=Nellie |title=''Watchmen'': James Wolk Cast In Recurring Role On HBO Series |url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/watchmen-james-wolk-cast-hbo-keene-1202496442/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=November 6, 2018 |date=November 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190214124905/https://deadline.com/2018/11/watchmen-james-wolk-cast-hbo-keene-1202496442/ |archive-date=February 14, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hall |first1=Jacob |title=Exclusive: Jeremy Irons is Older Ozymandias in the 'Watchmen' TV Series, Jean Smart Joins the Cast as an FBI Agent |url=https://www.slashfilm.com/watchmen-ozymandias-jean-smart/ |website=[[/Film]] |accessdate=November 8, 2018 |date=November 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190203082231/https://www.slashfilm.com/watchmen-ozymandias-jean-smart/ |archive-date=February 3, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Andreeva |first1=Nellie |title=''Watchmen'': Jean Smart To Co-Star On HBO Series From Damon Lindelof |url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/watchmen-jean-smart-cast-hbo-series-damon-lindelof-1202498463/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=November 8, 2018 |date=November 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116034529/https://deadline.com/2018/11/watchmen-jean-smart-cast-hbo-series-damon-lindelof-1202498463/ |archive-date=November 16, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Nugent |first1=John |last2=Travis |first2=Ben |title=Watchmen: Tim Blake Nelson Reveals His Character In HBO Series \u2013 Exclusive |url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/watchmen-tim-blake-nelson-reveals-character-hbo-series-exclusive/ |website=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] |accessdate=November 10, 2018 |date=November 9, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181111001553/https://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/watchmen-tim-blake-nelson-reveals-character-hbo-series-exclusive/ |archive-date=November 11, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> and that Vickers and Mison would join the cast.<ref name=\"Ars Technica 2019-05-08\">{{cite web |url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2019/05/hbo-drops-first-teaser-for-its-upcoming-watchmen-series/ |title=HBO drops first teaser for its upcoming Watchmen series |last=Ouellette |first=Jennifer|author-link=Jennifer Ouellette |date=May 8, 2019 |website=[[Ars Technica]]|access-date=May 9, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190508223914/https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2019/05/hbo-drops-first-teaser-for-its-upcoming-watchmen-series/|archive-date=May 8, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In January 2019, it was announced that [[Hong Chau]] and [[Dustin Ingram]] had been cast in recurring roles.<ref>{{cite web |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |title=''Watchmen'': Hong Chau Joins Cast Of HBO Series |url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/watchmen-hong-chau-cast-hbo-series-lady-t-1202533904/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=January 11, 2019 |date=January 11, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190112150243/https://deadline.com/2019/01/watchmen-hong-chau-cast-hbo-series-lady-t-1202533904/ |archive-date= January 12, 2019 |url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Petski |first=Denise |title=''Watchmen'': Dustin Ingram To Recur On HBO Series |url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/watchmen-dustin-ingram-recur-hbo-series-damon-lindelof-1202541172/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=January 24, 2019 |date=January 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190125020626/https://deadline.com/2019/01/watchmen-dustin-ingram-recur-hbo-series-damon-lindelof-1202541172/ |archive-date=January 25, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe performances of the cast during the pilot and other scenes influenced later episodes in the show's writing. When filming Irons for the pilot, Lindelof and his team found he took the character of Veidt in a comedic direction, something not suggested by the limited series. They recognized that this was \"a slightly absurd and ridiculous treatment of the character\" that worked for Veidt's role within the show, and stuck with it in writing the later episodes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/watchmen-season-finale-explained-damon-lindelof-see-how-they-fly-1262837 |title='Watchmen' Season Finale: Damon Lindelof Breaks Down That All-Powerful Ending |first=Josh |last=Wigler |date=December 15, 2019 |accessdate=December 17, 2019 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref>\n\nWhile reports in July 2019 suggested that actor [[Robert Redford]] would play a fictionalized version of himself in the series,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tvweb.com/watchmen-tv-show-robert-redford-president/ |title=Watchmen Elects Robert Redford as President of the United States |date=July 26, 2019 |website=TVweb.com |accessdate=July 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726201508/https://tvweb.com/watchmen-tv-show-robert-redford-president/|archive-date=July 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Lindelof affirmed later that the real Redford would not be appearing in the show; the use of Redford is a tribute to the \"[[Doomsday Clock (comics)|Doomsday Clock]]\" comic where it is suggested that Redford was positioning himself for President, in much the same way actor [[Ronald Reagan]] became President.<ref name=\"ew deep dive\"/>\n\n===Music===\n[[File:Reznor Ross G5 setup cropped tight.jpg|thumb|right|The music for the series is composed by Trent Reznor (left) and Atticus Ross]]\n[[Trent Reznor]] and [[Atticus Ross]] of [[Nine Inch Nails]] were announced as the series' composers on September 20, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pedersen |first1=Erik |title=''Watchmen'': Trent Reznor & Atticus Ross To Compose Music For Damon Lindelof's HBO Series |url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/watchmen-trent-reznor-atticus-ross-to-compose-music-for-damon-lindelofs-hbo-series-1202468375/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=September 20, 2018 |date=September 20, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011142449/https://deadline.com/2018/09/watchmen-trent-reznor-atticus-ross-to-compose-music-for-damon-lindelofs-hbo-series-1202468375/ |archive-date=October 11, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> In considering the series music, Lindelof had considered using Reznor and Ross as they had not composed for television before. By coincidence, when Lindelof suggested the pair to HBO, HBO reported that the two had been in contact with the network about doing the music just a few days prior, as they were big fans of ''Watchmen''.<ref name=\"ew deep dive\"/> Reznor stated he and Ross were also fans of Lindelof's previous work and thus sought to offer their services for the show.<ref name=\"rs reznor\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/trent-reznor-watchmen-pretty-hate-machine-interview-905456/ |title=Trent Reznor on ''Watchmen'' Soundtrack, Nine Inch Nails' 'Pretty Hate Machine' Turning 30 |first=Kory |last=Grow |date=November 5, 2019 |accessdate=November 5, 2019 |work=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref> Reznor and Ross had already prepared pieces for the pilot episode prior to filming, allowing Lindelof to better incorporate it into the pilot.<ref name=\"ew deep dive\"/> According to Reznor, their initial compositions were set for \"an aggressive, sort of sleazy tone\" for the show, but adapted to the series as it changed tone throughout the first season.<ref name=\"rs reznor\"/>\n\nIn addition to new compositions, the show employed licensed music selected by music supervisor [[Liza Richardson]]. The songs frequently tied in with the narrative elements of the show, which was also done in the limited series. Several songs from the musical ''[[Oklahoma!]]'' are used, given the show's setting in Tulsa. \"[[A God Walks into Abar]]\", in which the blue-skinned Doctor Manhattan is introduced, used a number of songs themed around the color blue, such as \"[[Rhapsody in Blue]]\" and \"[[The Blue Danube]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.spin.com/2019/12/watchmen-music-songs-show/ |title=Watchmen's On-the-Nose Music Supervision Was a Sly and Fitting Tribute to the Original Comic |first=Will |last=Gottsegen |date=December 16, 2019 |accessdate=December 17, 2019 |work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]}}</ref> The final episode \"[[See How They Fly]]\" incorporates many of the unusual phrases from [[The Beatles]]' \"[[I Am the Walrus]]\" into its visual elements.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/12/watchmen-finale-song-i-am-the-eggman-walrus-who-sings-easter-eggs-damon-lindelof |title=The Final Watchmen Easter Egg Goes Deeper Than You Think |first=Joanna |last=Robinson |date=December 15, 2019 |accessdate=December 15, 2019 |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]}}</ref>\n\nTying in with the first season, Reznor and Ross released three albums of music from the show on both vinyl albums and through streaming services.<ref name=\"rs music release\"/> The [[Watchmen: Volume 1|first volume]] was released on November 4,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.slashfilm.com/watchmen-soundtrack-streaming/ |title=''Watchmen'' Soundtrack From Trent Reznor and Atticus Ross is Now Streaming |first=Chris |last=Evangelista |date=November 5, 2019 |accessdate=November 5, 2019 |work=[[Slash Film]]}}</ref> the [[Watchmen: Volume 2|second]] on November 25, and the [[Watchmen: Volume 3|third]] on December 16, 2019.<ref name=\"rs music release\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/trent-reznor-atticus-watchmen-soundtrack-901981/ |title=Trent Reznor, Atticus Ross Plot Three-Volume ''Watchmen'' Soundtrack Albums |first=Kory |last=Glow |date=October 21, 2019 |accessdate=October 22, 2019 |work=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/12/trent-reznor-atticus-ross-soundtrack-watchmen-vol-3/ |title=Trent Reznor and Atticus Ross close their soundtrack trilogy with Watchmen Vol. 3: Stream |first=Wren |last=Graves |date=December 18, 2019 |accessdate=December 18, 2019 |work=[[Consequence of Sound]]}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:Penrhyn Castle - geograph.org.uk - 47395.jpg|thumb|right|[[Penrhyn Castle]] in Wales was used for the scenes with Veidt.]]\n\n[[Principal photography]] for the pilot commenced May 30, 2018, and lasted through June 2, 2018, in [[Cedartown]], Georgia. Filming began on the 97th anniversary of the start of the riots during the second day of the production schedule on May 31.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Myrick |first1=Kevin |title=Film crews to shut down Main Street at end of May |url=http://www.northwestgeorgianews.com/polk_standard_journal/news/local/film-crews-to-shut-down-main-street-at-end-of/article_bb0761d4-520c-11e8-a438-8f91a2338e4e.html |accessdate=December 28, 2019 |work=The Polk County Standard Journal |date=May 7, 2018}}</ref>  Throughout the month, filming occurred in additional Georgia cities and towns, including [[Macon, Georgia|Macon]], [[Fayetteville, Georgia|Fayetteville]], [[Newnan, Georgia|Newnan]], [[Palmetto, Georgia|Palmetto]], [[Brooks, Georgia|Brooks]], Griffin, Georgia and [[Tucker, Georgia|Tucker]].<ref name=\"atlmag filming\">{{cite web |last1=Walljasper |first1=Matt |title=What's filming in Atlanta now? HBO's Watchmen, Clint Eastwood's The Mule, Stranger Things, Stuber, and more |url=http://www.atlantamagazine.com/news-culture-articles/whats-filming-atlanta-now-hbos-watchmen-clint-eastwoods-mule-stranger-things-stuber/ |website=[[Atlanta (magazine)|Atlanta]] |accessdate=July 1, 2018 |date=June 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829224059/http://www.atlantamagazine.com/news-culture-articles/whats-filming-atlanta-now-hbos-watchmen-clint-eastwoods-mule-stranger-things-stuber/ |archive-date=August 29, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> In October 2018, filming for the remainder of the first season began in Georgia. Filming locations that month included Palmetto, [[Brookhaven, Georgia|Brookhaven]], [[Peachtree City, Georgia|Peachtree City]], [[Decatur, Georgia|Decatur]], and the [[Chamblee station|MARTA station]] in [[Chamblee, Georgia|Chamblee]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Walljasper |first1=Matt |title=What's filming in Atlanta now? Doctor Sleep, The Banker, Stranger Things, Avengers, Watchmen, and more |url=https://www.atlantamagazine.com/news-culture-articles/whats-filming-in-atlanta-now-doctor-sleep-the-banker-stranger-things-avengers-watchmen-and-more/ |website=Atlanta |accessdate=November 1, 2018 |date=October 29, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116171615/https://www.atlantamagazine.com/news-culture-articles/whats-filming-in-atlanta-now-doctor-sleep-the-banker-stranger-things-avengers-watchmen-and-more/ |archive-date=November 16, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> In November 2018, shooting moved to locales such as Palmetto, Chamblee, [[McDonough, Georgia|McDonough]], and the [[West Lake station (MARTA)|West Lake MARTA station]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Walljasper |first=Matt |title=What's filming in Atlanta now? Limited Partners, Watchmen, Stranger Things, plus unpacking the #BoycottGeorgia movement |url=https://www.atlantamagazine.com/news-culture-articles/whats-filming-in-atlanta-now-limited-partners-watchmen-stranger-things-plus-unpacking-the-boycottgeorgia-movement/ |website=Atlanta |accessdate=December 26, 2018 |date=November 29, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181201142206/https://www.atlantamagazine.com/news-culture-articles/whats-filming-in-atlanta-now-limited-partners-watchmen-stranger-things-plus-unpacking-the-boycottgeorgia-movement/ |archive-date= December 1, 2018 |url-status= live}}</ref> In December 2018, the production was working out of [[Union City, Georgia|Union City]], [[Newnan, Georgia|Newnan]], and the [[Georgia World Congress Center]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Walljasper |first=Matt |title=What's filming in Atlanta now? Undercover Brother 2, Limited Partners, Watchmen, Dolly Parton's Heartstrings, and more |url=https://www.atlantamagazine.com/news-culture-articles/whats-filming-in-atlanta-now-undercover-brother-2-limited-partners-watchmen-dolly-partons-heartstrings-and-more/ |website=Atlanta |accessdate=December 26, 2018 |date=December 20, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181224220207/https://www.atlantamagazine.com/news-culture-articles/whats-filming-in-atlanta-now-undercover-brother-2-limited-partners-watchmen-dolly-partons-heartstrings-and-more/ |archive-date=December 24, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Interior shooting was filmed at Atlanta Metro Studios in Union City.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ajc.com/blog/radiotvtalk/hbo-watchmen-mostly-shot-georgia-but-not-that-castle/nkgVzbJvgpjS9RxAXXJg7L/ |title=HBO's ''Watchmen'' mostly shot in Georgia \u2013 but not that castle |first=Rodney |last=Ho |date=October 19, 2019 |accessdate=December 9, 2019 |work=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]}}</ref>\n\nFilming of the country manor scenes was treated as a separate production, similar in nature to the ''Tales of the Black Freighter'' comic narrative within the original ''Watchmen'' graphic novel. Filming of these scenes took place in September 2018 in [[Wales]] at the [[Penrhyn Castle]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thebangoraye.com/hbos-watchmen-filmed-at-penrhyn-castle-to-be-released-in-2019/ |title=HBO's Watchmen filmed at Penrhyn Castle to be released in 2019 |website=The Bangor Aye |date=April 28, 2019 |accessdate=October 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ajc.com/blog/radiotvtalk/hbo-watchmen-mostly-shot-georgia-but-not-that-castle/nkgVzbJvgpjS9RxAXXJg7L/ |title=HBO's ''Watchmen'' mostly shot in Georgia \u2013 but not that castle |website=Atlanta News Now |first=Rodney |last=Ho |date=October 19, 2019 |accessdate=October 22, 2019}}</ref> These were completed before most of the remaining episode scripts were finished, according to actor Tom Mison.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/watchmen-mr-phillips-tom-mison-death-explained-1250699 |title='Watchmen' Star on How That Fiery Death Raises an Existential Question: \"What is Life?\" |first=Josh |last=Wigler |date=October 29, 2019 |accessdate=October 29, 2019 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref> According to Lindelof, these scenes are \"the idea is doing an escape story with Adrian Veidt that's more like [[Wile E. Coyote and the Road Runner]] than it was like ''[[Escape from Alcatraz (film)|Escape from Alcatraz]]'', that felt too delicious to not do\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://collider.com/watchmen-adrian-veidt-explained/ |title=Damon Lindelof Explains Why ''Watchmen'' Portrays Adrian Veidt as [SPOILER] |first=Adam |last=Chitwood |date=November 6, 2019 |accessdate=November 6, 2019 |work=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]}}</ref> Until the third episode, HBO did not identify Irons' character as Veidt, but only as \"Lord of a Country Manor\". Lindelof chose to keep Veidt's identity a secret in part to avoid having the show be considered a sequel of the comic, as well as in keeping with the storytelling mystery used by the comic, in which the identity of Rorschach is not revealed until midway through the series.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/hbos-watchmen-ozymandias-theory-gets-apparent-conf/1100-6471322/ |title=HBO's Watchmen Ozymandias Theory Gets Apparent Confirmation From Damon Lindelof |first=Michael |last=Rougeau |date=November 8, 2019 |accessdate=November 8, 2019 |work=[[GameSpot]]}}</ref>\n\n===Marketing===\nThe first teaser for the series, named \"Tick Tock\", first aired on May 8, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/05/08/hbo-watchmen-teaser-trailer/ |title=Tick tock! HBO's Watchmen teaser trailer counts down to a reckoning |first=Nick |last=Romano |date=May 8, 2019 |accessdate=December 14, 2019 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]}}</ref>\n\nWith release of each episode, HBO released additional content on a special site named \"Peteypedia\", a collection of files written in-universe by Dale Petey and from other excerpts. Peteypedia was developed after most of the filming was completed, with writer [[Jeff Jensen]] overseeing it. The writing team were aware they had developed too much information that would fit into the broadcast show and debated how to present this, including as post-credit scenes or through [[social media]]. At the same time, HBO was working with Reznor and Ross on how to release the albums and were considering including additional [[liner note]]s in the vinyl releases, which included the additional background material the writers had developed. This led to creating reports and clippings similar to those presented in the original ''Watchmen'' comic, and presenting this as part of Peteypedia.<ref name=\"vulture peteypedia\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/12/how-watchmen-made-peteypedia.html |title=How Watchmen Built Out Its Universe With Peteypedia |first=Jackson |last=McHenry |date=December 20, 2019 |accessdate=December 23, 2019 |work=[[Vulture (magazine)|Vulture]]}}</ref> Peteypedia allowed them, for example, to explain Laurie's trajectory from being the second Silk Spectre and fighting crime with Nite Owl at the end of the comic series, to becoming an FBI agent, elements of this that they had written briefly into the show but did not have broadcast time to spell out.<ref name=\"vulture peteypedia\"/> They also tied elements back to the original comic. Of note is the fictional novel ''Fogdancing'' written in-universe by Max Shea, one of the people that Veidt had used to device the squid attack in 1985. Jensen said that in the extra material with the graphic novel, ''Fogdancing'' had been made into a film at least twice, so the writers considered the work to be seminal to the characters in the television series, having the book appear at least twice during the show. Jensen created a whole plot summary of the work based on minimal clues from the comic, making the work to be about super-soldiers and having it tie to the idea of the ''Watchmen'' superhero culture.<ref name=\"vulture peteypedia\"/>\n\n===Continuation===\nWhile HBO had not yet confirmed a second season following the show's broadcast, Lindelof stated that if there were, he would not likely be back for it, but instead have another producer step forward to tell another story set in this universe. Lindelof said he felt that the show was \"not my story\" and that \"These nine episodes are sort of everything that I have to say at this point about ''Watchmen''\".<ref name=\"ahs\">{{cite web |last=Colburn |first=Randall |title=Ryan Murphy almost had a Watchmen cameo as Ryan Murphy, creator of American Hero Story |url=https://news.avclub.com/ryan-murphy-almost-had-a-watchmen-cameo-as-ryan-murphy-1839234510 |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=October 21, 2019 |accessdate=November 24, 2019}}</ref> Lindelof created the first season to be a complete story, in the same manner that each season of ''[[Fargo (TV series)|Fargo]]'' and ''[[True Detective]]'' were each self-contained stories.<ref>{{cite web |last=Wood |first=Tom |title=Watchmen Creator Damon Lindelof Says There Is More To Come |url=https://www.ladbible.com/entertainment/tv-and-film-damon-lindelof-says-there-will-definitely-be-more-watchmen-in-future-20191118 |work=[[LADbible]] |date=November 22, 2019 |accessdate=December 4, 2019}}</ref> Following the broadcast of the season one finale, Lindelof still said that the story he told during the season was everything he could put forward about ''Watchmen'', with a definitive beginning, middle, and end. However, he agreed with HBO that ''Watchmen'' should be treated as a continuing series, and did not rule out returning, but would want to have time to develop a similar complete story before committing.<ref>{{cite web |last=Vary |first=Adam |title=''Watchmen'' Showrunner Damon Lindelof Says He Could Return for Season 2 |url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/watchmen-season-2-damon-lindelof-finale-1203441149/ |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=December 16, 2019 |accessdate=December 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBy January 2020, Lindelof stated he had passed on a second season but gave his blessing to anyone that followed him as showrunner. HBO's programming chief Casey Bloys stated with regards a second season that \"It would be hard to imagine doing it without Damon involved in some way\", while not altogether dismissing the possibility of the concept of one.<ref name=\"usatoday nos2\">{{cite web |last=Levin |first=Gary |title=HBO won't pursue second season of 'Watchmen' after creator bows out |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/tv/2020/01/16/watchmen-second-hbo-season-wont-happen-after-creator-bails/4491269002/ |work=[[USA Today]] |date=January 16, 2020 |accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref> Due to this, HBO reclassified ''Watchmen'' as a limited series in February 2020, with the potential for additional installments.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/watchmen-limited-series-1203510971/ |title=HBO Reclassifies \u2018Watchmen\u2019 as a Limited Series, Including \u2018Possible Future Installments\u2019 |first=Adam |last=Vary |date=February 21, 2020 |accessdate=February 21, 2020 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>\n\n==Broadcast and distribution==\nThe series was first broadcast on the HBO network from October 20 through December 15, 2019. In New Zealand, ''Watchmen'' is distributed exclusively by [[Neon (New Zealand)|Neon]], [[Sky (New Zealand)|Sky Television]]'s subscription television series.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Brooks |first1=Sam |title=What you need to know before you watch Watchmen |url=https://thespinoff.co.nz/tv/neon/24-10-2019/what-you-need-to-know-before-you-watch-watchmen/ |accessdate=January 16, 2020 |work=[[The Spinoff]] |date=October 24, 2019}}</ref> In Australia, the series is distributed by [[Foxtel]]'s streaming service.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ma |first1=Wenlei |title=HBO series Watchmen drops new trailer |url=https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/tv-shows/hbo-series-watchmen-drops-new-trailer/news-story/b86e5b553bf0236cf9f902beb6cfdd1d |accessdate=January 16, 2020 |work=[[News.com.au]] |date=September 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe series was released onto digital media for purchase or streaming in December 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.comingsoon.net/tv/news/1114951-hbos-watchmen-season-1-out-on-digital-today |title=HBO\u2019s Watchmen Season 1 Out on Digital Today! |first=Kyle |last=Hemmert |date=December 16, 2019 |accessdate=February 8, 2020 |work=ComingSoon.net}}</ref> [[Warner Bros. Home Entertainment]] will release the series on Blu-ray under the title ''Watchmen: An HBO Limited Series'' on June 2, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.blu-ray.com/news/?id=26413 |title=Watchmen: An HBO Limited Series Blu-ray |date=February 14, 2020 |accessdate=February 15, 2020 |work=Blu-ray.com}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical response===\n<!--AUDIENCE RECEPTION AND RATINGS: Do not include them! Wikipedia does not support user-generated content in its articles, and thus audience ratings cannot be included. Please refer to the talk page before proceeding to edit this section, and view the multiple discussions raised on the topic. No consensus has been formed to allow this article to differ from Wikipedia's guidelines and policies by including such content. Additions of audience ratings will be reverted.-->\n\n{{Quote box\n|width=35%\n|quote=\"I wanted to kind of make this like, 'Yeah, this is what [[Batman]] would be in the real world.' But I had forgotten that actually to a lot of comic fans that smelling, not having a girlfriend\u2014these are actually kind of heroic. So actually, sort of, Rorschach became the most popular character in ''Watchmen''. I meant him to be a bad example, but I have people come up to me in the street saying, 'I am Rorschach! That is my story!' And I'll be thinking, 'Yeah, great, can you just keep away from me and never come anywhere near me again for as long as I live?'\"\n|source=\u2014[[Alan Moore]], original ''[[Watchmen]]'' creator on [[Rorschach (character)|Rorschach]]'s reception<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/tv/a29565670/watchmen-hbo-backlash-controversy-white-supremacy/ |title=The Right-Wing Troll Backlash Against HBO's Watchmen Is Hilariously Stupid |first=Matt |last=Miller |date=October 24, 2019 |website=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |accessdate=November 5, 2019}}</ref>\n|align=right\n}}\n\n{{Quote box\n|width=35%\n|quote=\"I love Rorschach. I loved him as a 13-year-old, and I still love him. When you see the tears streaming down his face when his mask is pulled off, one of the cops is saying, \u201cThis little runt is wearing lifts.\u201d It just breaks my heart every time. I have such empathy and compassion for this guy who\u2019s losing. The world is sickening, and there\u2019s nothing that he can do to stop it.\"\n|source=\u2014[[Damon Lindelof]], ''[[Watchmen]]'' television show creator on the appeal of [[Rorschach (character)|Rorschach]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/10/watchmen-hbo-damon-lindelof.html |title=Like It or Not, Damon Lindelof Made His Own Watchmen |first=Abraham |last=Riesman |date=October 17, 2019 |website=[[Vulture (magazine)|Vulture]] |accessdate=January 3, 2020}}</ref>\n|align=right\n}}\n\n''Watchmen'' has received widespread critical acclaim. On [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the series has a 96% \"certified fresh\" rating based on 97 reviews, with an average rating of 8.53/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"Bold and bristling, ''Watchmen'' isn't always easy viewing, but by adding new layers of cultural context and a host of complex characters it expertly builds on its source material to create an impressive identity of its own.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/watchmen/s01 |title=Watchmen: Season 1 (2019) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=November 14, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], it has a weighted average score of 85 out of 100, based on 33 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/watchmen-2019/season-1 |title=Watchmen (2019): Season 1 |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=November 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nRotten Tomatoes' audience score is markedly lower than the critics' consensus, with several news outlets reporting that the site was [[review bomb]]ed. ''Esquire'' writer Matt Miller wrote that \"far-right trolls\" have artificially deflated the audience score.<ref name=\"dailybeast review bomb\"/><ref name=\"Moore Interview 2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.twomorrows.com/comicbookartist/articles/09moore.html |last=Knutson |first=Jon B. |title=Toasting Absent Heroes |date=June 16, 2000 |publisher=[[TwoMorrows Publishing]] |accessdate=March 8, 2013}}</ref> These outlets agree that the chief complaint among followers of the source material is that the image of fan-favorite character Rorschach is adopted by the Seventh Kavalry, a white supremacist organization.\n\nMany fans have agreed with the television series' use of Rorschach's image as an element in right-wing politics, citing Alan Moore's intention to use Rorschach to comment on what characters like Batman would be like in real life. Other fans have claimed that the show should conform to their interpretation of Rorschach as a straightforward hero.<ref name=\"dailybeast review bomb\">{{cite web |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/hbos-watchmen-pisses-off-comics-fanboys-its-woke-propaganda |title=Comics Fanboys Are Pissed About HBO's ''Watchmen'': It's 'Woke' Propaganda! |first=Kevin |last=Fallon |date=October 25, 2019 |accessdate=November 4, 2019 |work=[[The Daily Beast]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/10/26/hbo-watchmen-is-bombing-reviews-but-that-wont-scare-off-any-viewers.html |title=HBO's ''Watchmen'' is getting 'review bombed,' but that won't scare off any viewers |first=Daniel |last=Bukszpan |date=October 26, 2019 |accessdate=November 4, 2019 |work=[[CNBC]]}}</ref>\n\nIn response, Damon Lindelof stated that the show is not intended to portray Walter Kovacs, the original Rorschach, as a racist. At the New York Comic Con, he explained that Rorschach's journal had been misinterpreted by the ''New Frontiersman'' and that his image has been misappropriated by the Seventh Kavalry. \u201cHe\u2019s been dead for over 30 years,\" Lindelof clarified. \"He doesn\u2019t get to say, \u2018You misunderstood me. No, I wasn\u2019t a white supremacist.\u2019 They decided what he was.\u201d<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.inverse.com/article/59815-watchmen-damon-lindelof-on-white-surprmacist-adoption-of-rorshach |title='Watchmen' producer explains white supremacist \"appropriation\" of Rorshach |website=Inverse |first=Eric |last=Francisco |date=October 5, 2019 |accessdate=January 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Ratings===\n{{Television episode ratings\n| width = 99\n| noshare   = y\n\n| title1    = [[It's Summer and We're Running Out of Ice]]\n| date1     = October 20, 2019\n| rs1       = 0.3\n| viewers1  = 0.799<ref name=\"1.01\"/>\n| dvr1      = n/a\n| dvrv1     = n/a\n| total1    = n/a\n| totalv1   = n/a\n\n| title2    = [[Martial Feats of Comanche Horsemanship]]\n| date2     = October 27, 2019\n| rs2       = 0.3\n| viewers2  = 0.765<ref name=\"1.02\"/>\n| dvr2      = n/a\n| dvrv2     = 0.704\n| total2    = n/a\n| totalv2   = 1.470<ref>{{cite