{"title_page": "Abraham Berge", "text_new": "{{Infobox Politician\n|name=Abraham Theodor Berge\n|image=Abraham Theodor Berge, 1912, L. Szacinski (firmaet), Oslo Museum, OB.SZ22556.jpg\n| office = [[Prime Minister of Norway]]\n| term_start = 30 May 1923\n| term_end = 25 July 1924\n| predecessor = [[Otto Bahr Halvorsen]]\n| successor = [[Johan Ludwig Mowinckel]]\n| office2 = [[Minister of Finance (Norway)|Minister of Finance]]\n| term_start2 =23 March 1923\n| term_end2 = 25 July 1924\n| predecessor2 = [[Otto Albert Blehr]]\n| successor2 = [[Arnold Holmboe]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Otto Bahr Halvorsen]]<br>''Himself''\n| term_start3 = 2 February 1910\n| term_end3 = 20 February 1912\n| predecessor3 = [[Gunnar Knudsen]]\n| successor3 = [[Fredrik Ludvig Konow]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Wollert Konow (SB)|Wollert Konow]]\n| term_start4 = 7 November 1906\n| term_end4 = 23 October 1907\n| predecessor4 = [[Edvard Hagerup Bull]]\n| successor4 = [[Johan Magnus Halvorsen]]\n| primeminister4 = [[Christian Michelsen]]\n| office5 = [[Ministry of Education and Research (Norway)|Minister of Church and Education]]\n| term_start5 =23 October  1907\n| term_end5 = 19 March 1908\n| predecessor5 = [[Otto Jensen]]\n| successor5 = [[Karl Seip]]\n| primeminister5 = [[J\u00f8rgen L\u00f8vland]]\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date|1851|8|20|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Lyngdal]], {{flag|Norway|1844}}\n|death_date  = {{Death date and age|1936|7|10|1851|8|20|df=y}}\n|death_place = [[T\u00f8nsberg]], {{flag|Norway}}\n|nationality = [[Norway|Norwegian]]\n| awards = [[File:St. Olavs Orden stripe.svg|25px]] [[Order of St. Olav]]\n| party = [[Free-minded Liberal Party]]\n| otherparty = [[Liberal Party (Norway)|Liberal Party]]\n| profession = \n*[[Teacher]]\n*[[Farmer]]\n*[[Politician|Statesman]]\n|monarch=[[Haakon VII]]}}\n'''Abraham Theodor Berge''' (20 August 1851 \u2013 10 July 1936) was [[Prime Minister of Norway]] from 1923 to 1924. He was a teacher and civil servant who represented [[Liberal Party (Norway)|Venstre]], the social liberal party, and later [[Frisinnede Venstre]], a right-of-centre party. <ref>{{cite web\n|url=  https://www.regjeringen.no/en/the-government/previous-governments/ministries-and-offices/offices/prime-minister-since-1814/abraham-theodor-berge/id463361/  |title=   Abraham Berge, Prime Minister 1923 - 1924|publisher= Government.no |accessdate= June 10,  2016}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nBerge was born at [[Lyngdal]] in Lister og Mandals amt (present-day [[Vest-Agder]]), Norway . He was the son of Johan Tobias Johnsen Berge (1813-1883) and Helene Andreasdatter Kvalsvig. He attended the teacher's course offered by Reinert R\u00f8dland in [[Lyngdal]]. In 1867, Berge became teacher at the Nordbygda skole in [[Vanse]]. He also served as sheriff in Vanse from 1904 to 1908. Berge was appointed [[County governor (Norway)|County Governor]] in [[Vestfold]] in 1908, a position  he held until 1924 \n<ref>{{cite web|url =https://lokalhistoriewiki.no/wiki/Abraham_Berge |title= Abraham Berge\n|publisher =lokalhistoriewiki |accessdate= April  1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBerge started his political career in Lista in the present-day municipality of [[Farsund]], where he was in 1882 elected mayor. From here he went on to the Norwegian [[Storting|Parliament]] in 1891. He served, in different periods, as both [[Minister of Culture (Norway)|Minister of Culture and Church Affairs]] and [[Minister of Finance (Norway)|Minister of Finance]]. Then, after a 10-year absence from politics, he became again Minister of Finance, and later also Prime Minister, when sitting Prime Minister [[Otto Bahr Halvorsen]] died. He resigned this post as the result of the defeat in a vote to lift [[prohibition]].<ref>{{cite web|url=  https://nbl.snl.no/Abraham_Berge|title=   Abraham Berge, L\u00e6rer, Politiker|publisher=  Norsk biografisk leksikon \n|author= Svein Carstens |accessdate= June 10,  2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1926 he became the only Norwegian prime minister to ever be [[Impeachment (Norway)|impeached]]. The charge was withholding information relating to the government rescue of a bank threatened by [[bankruptcy]]. However, he was acquitted in 1927, along with the six ministers who stood trial alongside him.<ref>{{cite web|url=  https://snl.no/Abraham_Theodor_Berge|title=    Abraham Theodor Berge|publisher=    Store norske leksikon \n|accessdate= June 10,  2016}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n* ''Listerlandets kystv\u00e6rn og kaperfart 1807\u201314'' (T\u00f8nsberg 1914) and ''Lista. En bygdebok'' (T\u00f8nsberg 1926). Both books reprinted 2006 by Klokkhammer Forlag AS.\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Start box}}\n{{S-off}}\n{{Succession box | before=[[Otto Bahr Halvorsen]]| title=[[List of Norwegian Prime Ministers|Prime Minister of Norway]] | years=1923&ndash;1924 | after=[[Johan Ludwig Mowinckel]]}}\n{{End box}}\n{{NorwegianPrimeMinisters}}\n{{Liberal Left Party}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Berge, Abraham}}\n[[Category:1851 births]]\n[[Category:1936 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Farsund]]\n[[Category:Norwegian educators]]\n[[Category:County Governors of Norway]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (Norway) politicians]]\n[[Category:Ministers of Finance of Norway]]\n[[Category: Recipients of the St. Olav's Medal]]\n{{Norway-politician-1850s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Politician\n|name=Abraham Theodor Berge\n|image=Abraham Theodor Berge, 1912, L. Szacinski (firmaet), Oslo Museum, OB.SZ22556.jpg\n| office = [[Prime Minister of Norway]]\n| term_start = 30 May 1923\n| term_end = 25 July 1924\n| predecessor = [[Otto Bahr Halvorsen]]\n| successor = [[Johan Ludwig Mowinckel]]\n| office2 = [[Minister of Finance (Norway)|Minister of Finance]]\n| term_start2 =23 March 1923\n| term_end2 = 25 July 1924\n| predecessor2 = [[Otto Albert Blehr]]\n| successor2 = [[Arnold Holmboe]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Otto Bahr Halvorsen]]<br>''Himself''\n| term_start3 = 2 February 1910\n| term_end3 = 20 February 1912\n| predecessor3 = [[Gunnar Knudsen]]\n| successor3 = [[Fredrik Ludvig Konow]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Wollert Konow (SB)|Wollert Konow]]\n| term_start4 = 7 November 1906\n| term_end4 = 23 October 1907\n| predecessor4 = [[Edvard Hagerup Bull]]\n| successor4 = [[Johan Magnus Halvorsen]]\n| primeminister4 = [[Christian Michelsen]]\n| office5 = [[Ministry of Education and Research (Norway)|Minister of Church and Education]]\n| term_start5 =23 October  1907\n| term_end5 = 19 March 1908\n| predecessor5 = [[Otto Jensen]]\n| successor5 = [[Karl Seip]]\n| primeminister5 = [[J\u00f8rgen L\u00f8vland]]\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date|1851|8|20|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Lyngdal]], {{flag|Norway|1844}}\n|death_date  = {{Death date and age|1936|7|10|1851|8|20|df=y}}\n|death_place = [[T\u00f8nsberg]], {{flag|Norway}}\n|nationality = [[Norway|Norwegian]]\n| awards = [[File:St. Olavs Orden stripe.svg|25px]] [[Order of St. Olav]]\n| party = [[Free-minded Liberal Party]]\n| otherparty = [[Liberal Party (Norway)|Liberal Party]]\n| profession = \n*[[Teacher]]\n*[[Farmer]]\n*[[Politician|Statesman]]\n|monarch=[[Haakon VII]]}}\n'''Abraham Theodor Berge''' (20 August 1851 \u2013 10 July 1936) was [[Prime Minister of Norway]] from 1923 to 1924. He was a teacher and civil servant who represented [[Liberal Party (Norway)|Venstre]], the social liberal party, and later [[Frisinnede Venstre]], a right-of-centre party. <ref>{{cite web\n|url=  https://www.regjeringen.no/en/the-government/previous-governments/ministries-and-offices/offices/prime-minister-since-1814/abraham-theodor-berge/id463361/  |title=   Abraham Berge, Prime Minister 1923 - 1924|publisher= Government.no |accessdate= June 10,  2016}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nBerge was born at [[Lyngdal]] in Lister og Mandals amt (present-day [[Vest-Agder]]) , Norway . He was the son of Johan Tobias Johnsen Berge (1813-1883) and Helene Andreasdatter Kvalsvig. He attended the teacher's course offered by Reinert R\u00f8dland in [[Lyngdal]]. In 1867, Berge became teacher at the Nordbygda skole in [[Vanse]]. He also served as sheriff in Vanse from 1904 to 1908. Berge was appointed [[County governor (Norway)|County Governor]] in [[Vestfold]] in 1908, a position  he held until 1924 \n<ref>{{cite web|url =https://lokalhistoriewiki.no/wiki/Abraham_Berge |title= Abraham Berge\n|publisher =lokalhistoriewiki |accessdate= April  1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBerge started his political career in Lista in the present-day municipality of [[Farsund]], where he was in 1882 elected mayor. From here he went on to the Norwegian [[Storting|Parliament]] in 1891. He served, in different periods, as both [[Minister of Culture (Norway)|Minister of Culture and Church Affairs]] and [[Minister of Finance (Norway)|Minister of Finance]]. Then, after a 10-year absence from politics, he became again Minister of Finance, and later also Prime Minister, when sitting Prime Minister [[Otto Bahr Halvorsen]] died. He resigned this post as the result of the defeat in a vote to lift [[prohibition]].<ref>{{cite web|url=  https://nbl.snl.no/Abraham_Berge|title=   Abraham Berge, L\u00e6rer, Politiker|publisher=  Norsk biografisk leksikon \n|author= Svein Carstens |accessdate= June 10,  2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1926 he became the only Norwegian prime minister to ever be [[Impeachment (Norway)|impeached]]. The charge was withholding information relating to the government rescue of a bank threatened by [[bankruptcy]]. However, he was acquitted in 1927, along with the six ministers who stood trial alongside him.<ref>{{cite web|url=  https://snl.no/Abraham_Theodor_Berge|title=    Abraham Theodor Berge|publisher=    Store norske leksikon \n|accessdate= June 10,  2016}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n* ''Listerlandets kystv\u00e6rn og kaperfart 1807\u201314'' (T\u00f8nsberg 1914) and ''Lista. En bygdebok'' (T\u00f8nsberg 1926). Both books reprinted 2006 by Klokkhammer Forlag AS.\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Start box}}\n{{S-off}}\n{{Succession box | before=[[Otto Bahr Halvorsen]]| title=[[List of Norwegian Prime Ministers|Prime Minister 