{"title_page": "Aira Caldera", "text_new": "{{short description|A large flooded coastal volcanic caldera in the south of the island of Ky\u016bsh\u016b, Japan}}\n{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Aira\n\n| other_name = \u59f6\u826f\u30ab\u30eb\u30c7\u30e9\n| photo = sakura-jima_from_space.jpg\n| photo_caption = Space radar image of Aira Caldera, with [[Sakurajima]] in the bay formed by the caldera.\n| elevation = \n| prominence = \n| map = Japan\n| location = [[Kagoshima]], [[Japan]]\n| range = \n| coordinates = {{coord|31.667|N|130.667|E|type:mountain_scale:100000_source:dewiki|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| range_coordinates = \n| topo = \n| type = [[Caldera]]<br>[[Somma volcano]]\n| age = \n| last_eruption = ''c''. 22,000 years ago\n| first_ascent = \n| easiest_route = \n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Aira Caldera'''|\u59f6\u826f\u30ab\u30eb\u30c7\u30e9|Aira-Karudera}} is a gigantic [[volcanic]] [[caldera]] in the south of the [[Ky\u016bsh\u016b|island of Ky\u016bsh\u016b]]. It contains the post-caldera [[Sakurajima]], which is considered one of the most active volcanoes in [[Japan]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://volcano.si.edu/showreport.cfm?doi=GVP.WVAR20190911-282080|title=Global Volcanism Program {{!}} Report on Aira (Japan) \u2014 11\u201317 September 2019|website=volcano.si.edu|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n== Origin ==\nThe caldera was originally thought to have been created by a massive [[Types of volcanic eruption|eruption]], approximately 22,000 years ago.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Dinwiddie|first=Robert|title=Violent Earth: Volcanoes, Earthquakes, Hurricanes, Mudslides, Tsunamis|last2=Lamb|first2=Simon|last3=Ross|first3=Reynolds|date=2011|publisher=DK Publishing|year=|isbn=978-0-7566-8685-7|location=New York|pages=129}}</ref>  This eruption, whose widespread deposits are generically known as the Aira-Tanzawa tephra, is now thought to be rather older. The tephra eruption is estimated to have occurred 29,000 years ago.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Kawanabe|first=Hiroya|title=Lake Biwa: Interactions between Nature and People|last2=Nishino|first2=Machiko|last3=Maehata|first3=Masayoshi|date=2012|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|year=|isbn=978-94-007-1783-1|location=Dordrecht|pages=7}}</ref> The latest/best age estimates derive from cores from Lakes [[Biwa]] and [[Lake Suigetsu|Suigetsu]] indicate an age of 29,430-30,150 years ago.  Eruption of voluminous Ito [[pyroclastic flow]]s accompanied the formation of the 17 &times; 23&nbsp;km-wide Aira caldera.<ref name=\":0\" /> Together with a large [[pumice]] fall, these amounted to approximately 400&nbsp;km<sup>3</sup> of [[tephra]] ([[Volcanic Explosivity Index|VEI 7]]).\n\nThe major city of [[Kagoshima]] and the 16,000-year-old [[Sakurajima]] volcano lie within the caldera. Sakura-jima, one of Japan's most active volcanoes, is a post-caldera cone of the Aira caldera at the northern half of [[Kagoshima Bay]].\n[[File:Aira Caldera Relief Map, SRTM, English.jpg|thumb|160px|left|Relief Map]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{ cite journal | last = Smith | first = V.C. | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = 2013 | month = | title = Identification and correlation of visible tephras in the Lake Suigetsu SG06 sedimentary archive, Japan | journal = [[Quaternary Science Reviews]] | volume = 67 | issue =  | pages = 121\u2013137 | id = | url =  | accessdate = | quote = | doi =  | bibcode= }}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://volcano.si.edu/volcano.cfm?vn=282080 Aira] - Smithsonian Institution: Global Volcanism Program\n* [https://gbank.gsj.jp/volcano/Quat_Vol/volcano_data/K18.html Aira Caldera] - Geological Survey of Japan\n\n[[Category:Volcanoes of Kyushu]]\n[[Category:VEI-7 volcanoes]]\n[[Category:Calderas of Japan]]\n[[Category:Submarine calderas]]\n[[Category:Pleistocene volcanoes]]\n[[Category:Active volcanoes]]\n[[Category:Supervolcanoes]]\n[[Category:Volcanoes of Kagoshima Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Paleolithic Japan]]\n\n\n{{Kagoshima-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|A large flooded coastal volcanic caldera in the south of the island of Ky\u016bsh\u016b, Japan}}\n{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Aira \n\n| other_name = \u59f6\u826f\u30ab\u30eb\u30c7\u30e9\n| photo = sakura-jima_from_space.jpg\n| photo_caption = Space radar image of Aira Caldera, with [[Sakurajima]] in the bay formed by the caldera.\n| elevation = \n| prominence = \n| map = Japan\n| location = [[Kagoshima]], [[Japan]]\n| range = \n| coordinates = {{coord|31.667|N|130.667|E|type:mountain_scale:100000_source:dewiki|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| range_coordinates = \n| topo = \n| type = [[Caldera]]<br>[[Somma volcano]]\n| age = \n| last_eruption = ''c''. 22,000 years ago\n| first_ascent = \n| easiest_route = \n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Aira Caldera'''|\u59f6\u826f\u30ab\u30eb\u30c7\u30e9|Aira-Karudera}} is a gigantic [[volcanic]] [[caldera]] in the south of the [[Ky\u016bsh\u016b|island of Ky\u016bsh\u016b]]. It contains the post-caldera [[Sakurajima]], which is considered one of the most active volcanoes in [[Japan]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://volcano.si.edu/showreport.cfm?doi=GVP.WVAR20190911-282080|title=Global Volcanism Program {{!}} Report on Aira (Japan) \u2014 11 September-17 September 2019|website=volcano.si.edu|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n== Origin ==\nThe caldera was originally thought to have been created by a massive [[Types of volcanic eruption|eruption]], approximately 22,000 years ago<ref>{{Cite book|last=Dinwiddie|first=Robert|title=Violent Earth: Volcanoes, Earthquakes, Hurricanes, Mudslides, Tsunamis|last2=Lamb|first2=Simon|last3=Ross|first3=Reynolds|date=2011|publisher=DK Publishing|year=|isbn=978-0-7566-8685-7|location=New York|pages=129}}</ref>.  This eruption, whose widespread deposits are generically known as the Aira-Tanzawa tephra, is now thought to be rather older. The tephra eruption is estimated to have occurred 29,000 years ago.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Kawanabe|first=Hiroya|title=Lake Biwa: Interactions between Nature and People|last2=Nishino|first2=Machiko|last3=Maehata|first3=Masayoshi|date=2012|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|year=|isbn=978-94-007-1783-1|location=Dordrecht|pages=7}}</ref> The latest/best age estimates derive from cores from Lakes [[Biwa]] and [[Lake Suigetsu|Suigetsu]] indicate an age of 29,430-30,150 years ago.  Eruption of voluminous Ito [[pyroclastic flow]]s accompanied the formation of the 17 &times; 23&nbsp;km-wide Aira caldera.<ref name=\":0\" /> Together with a large [[pumice]] fall, these amounted to approximately 400&nbsp;km<sup>3</sup> of [[tephra]] ([[Volcanic Explosivity Index|VEI 7]]).\n\nThe major city of [[Kagoshima]] and the 16,000-year-old [[Sakurajima]] volcano lie within the caldera. Sakura-jima, one of Japan's most active volcanoes, is a post-caldera cone of the Aira caldera at the northern half of [[Kagoshima Bay]].\n[[File:Aira Caldera Relief Map, SRTM, English.jpg|thumb|160px|left|Relief Map]]\n\n==References==\n* {{ cite journal | last = Smith | first = V.C. | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = 2013 | month = | title = Identification and correlation of visible tephras in the Lake Suigetsu SG06 sedimentary archive, Japan | journal = [[Quaternary Science Reviews]] | volume = 67 | issue =  | pages = 121-137 | id = | url =  | accessdate = | quote = | doi =  | bibcode= }}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://volcano.si.edu/volcano.cfm?vn=282080 Aira] - Smithsonian Institution: Global Volcanism Program\n* [https://gbank.gsj.jp/volcano/Quat_Vol/volcano_data/K18.html Aira Caldera] - Geological Survey of Japan\n\n[[Category:Volcanoes of Kyushu]]\n[[Category:VEI-7 volcanoes]]\n[[Category:Calderas of Japan]]\n[[Category:Submarine calderas]]\n[[Category:Pleistocene volcanoes]]\n[[Category:Active volcanoes]]\n[[Category:Supervolcanoes]]\n[[Category:Volcanoes of Kagoshima Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Paleolithic Japan]]\n\n{{Kagoshima-geo-stub}}'\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aira_Caldera"}
{"title_page": "J\u00f8rgen L\u00f8vland", "text_new": "{{Infobox Prime Minister\n| name              = J\u00f8rgen L\u00f8vland\n| image             = J. L\u00f8vland - no-nb digifoto 20160420 00234 NB NS NM 10313 (cropped).jpg\n| order1            = \n| office1           = [[Prime Minister of Norway]]\n| term_start1       = 23 October 1907\n| term_end1         = 19 March 1908\n| monarch1          = [[Haakon VII of Norway|Haakon VII]]\n| governor-general1 = \n| predecessor1      = [[Christian Michelsen]]\n| successor1        = [[Gunnar Knudsen]]\n| office2= [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Norway)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]]\n| primeminister2= [[Christian Michelsen]] <br> Himself \n| term_start2= 7 June 1905 \n| term_end2= 19 March 1908 \n| predecessor2= Position established \n| successor2= [[Wilhelm Christopher Christophersen|Wilhelm Christophersen]] \n| office3= [[Minister of Education and Church Affairs (Norway)|Minister of Education and Church Affairs]]\n| term_start3= 26 October 1915\n| term_end3= 20 June 1920 \n| primeminister3= [[Gunnar Knudsen]]\n| predecessor3= [[Aasulv Olsen Bryggesaa|Aasulv Bryggesaa]]\n| successor3= [[Nils Riddervold Jensen]]\n| office4= [[Minister of Labour and Social Inclusion (Norway)|Minister of Labour]]\n| term_start4= 1 June 1900\n| term_end4= 21 October 1903\n| primeminister4= [[Johannes Steen]] <br> [[Otto Blehr]]\n| predecessor4= [[Hans Hein Theodor Nysom|Hans Nysom]]\n| successor4= [[Albert Hansen]]\n| term_start5= 17 February 1898 \n| term_end5= 28 February 1899 \n| primeminister5= [[Johannes Steen]]\n| predecessor5= [[Fredrik Stang Lund]] \n| successor5= Hans Nysom \n| birth_date        = 3 February 1848\n| birth_place       = [[Evje]], [[Norway]]\n| death_date        =  {{Death date and age|df=yes|1922|8|21|1848|2|3}}\n| death_place       = [[Oslo]], [[Norway]]\n| party             = [[Liberal Party of Norway|Liberal Party]]\n| alma_mater        = [[University of Agder|Kristiansand Teacher Training College]]\n| religion          =  \n| spouse            = \n}}\n'''J\u00f8rgen Gunnarsson L\u00f8vland''' (3 February 1848 &ndash; 21 August 1922) was a [[Norway|Norwegian]] educator and civil servant who served as [[Prime Minister]] of the [[Norwegian Parliament]] (1907-1908).<ref>{{cite web|url=   http://www.dokpro.uio.no/cgi-bin/stad/matr50|title=   J\u00f8rgen L\u00f8vland|publisher=    regjeringen.no   |date=   May 7, 2011  |accessdate= June 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:J\u00f8rgen L\u00f8vland, gravminne p\u00e5 V\u00e5r Frelsers gravlund, Oslo.JPG|thumb|Gravesite of J\u00f8rgen L\u00f8vland, V\u00e5r Frelsers gravlund in Oslo]]\n\n==Background==\nL\u00f8vland was born at Lauvland in  [[Evje]] (''Lauvland i Evje herad'') in [[Aust-Agder]], Norway. He came from a farming family. He graduated from [[Kristiansand Teacher Training College|Christianssands Stifts Seminarium]] teachers\u2019 seminary  in 1865. He worked  as primary school teacher in [[Christianssand]] (1866-1878) and then as headmaster in [[Setesdal]] (1878-1884). From 1884 to 1892 he was also editor of ''Christianssands Stiftsavis''.<ref>{{cite web|url=   https://snl.no/J%25C3%25B8rgen_Gunnarson_L%25C3%25B8vland\n|title=   J\u00f8rgen Gunnarson L\u00f8vland|publisher= Store norske leksikon |author= Magnus A. Mardal |accessdate= June 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nHe represented the Liberal party at the Norwegian Parliament (''Storting'') 1886-1888 and again in 1892\u20131898.  He was Minister of Labour (1898\u20131899, 1900\u20131902, 1902\u20131903), a member of the Council of State Division in [[Stockholm]] (1899\u20131900), Minister of Foreign Affairs (1905 and 1905\u20131907), Prime Minister and Minister of Foreign Affairs (1907\u20131908), and Minister of Education and Church Affairs (1915\u20131920). In 1905 became the  prime minister in Stockholm. He was chair of the Norwegian government of [[Christian Michelsen]]. In October 1907, L\u00f8vland took over as Norwegian Prime Minister when Michelsen resigned. L\u00f8vland resigned the position in March 1908.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsd.uib.no/polsys/index.cfm?urlname=&lan=&MenuItem=N1_1&ChildItem=&State=collapse&UttakNr=33&person=11942|title = J\u00f8rgen Gunnarson L\u00f8vland|publisher =   Norsk samfunnsvitenskapelig datatjeneste AS |accessdate= June 10, 2016}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.regjeringen.no/en/the-government/previous-governments/governments/during-and-after-the-dissolution-of-the-/ministries-1905---1940/ministries-1905---1940/christian-michelsens-government-1905---1/id507098/   |title= Christian Michelsen's Government \n|publisher =Regjeringen|accessdate= April  1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Norwegian Nobel Committee==\nL\u00f8vland was a member of the [[Norwegian Nobel Committee]] from the foundation in 1897 until his death in 1922. He was the committee's chairman  (1901\u20131921).\n<ref>{{cite web|url=    http://nobelpeaceprize.org/en_GB/nomination_intro/nomination_committee/|title =    Members of the first Norwegian Nobel Committee |publisher =   Nobel Committee|accessdate= June 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe was married to Mathilde L\u00f8vland (1851\u20131938). Following their deaths, both he and his wife were buried at [[V\u00e5r Frelsers gravlund]] in Oslo.\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Commons category|J\u00f8rgen L\u00f8vland}}\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160701054406/http://www.nppri.org/pdf/Vol1_No3.pdf  The Norwegian Nobel Institute Series] \n{{start box}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Christian Michelsen]]| title=[[Prime Minister of Norway]] | years=1907&ndash;1908| after=[[Gunnar Knudsen]]}}\n{{succession box | before=N/A| title=[[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Norway)|Norwegian Minister of Foreign Affairs]] | years=1905&ndash;1908 | after=[[Wilhelm Christopher Christophersen]]}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Aasulv Olsen Bryggesaa|Aasulv Bryggesaa]]| title=[[Minister of Education and Church Affairs (Norway)|Norwegian Minister of Education and Church Affairs]] | years=1915&ndash;1920 | after=[[Nils Riddervold Jensen]]}}\n{{s-culture}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Marius H\u00e6gstad]]| title=Chairman of [[Noregs M\u00e5llag]] | years=1909&ndash;1912| after=[[Nikolaus Gjelsvik]]}}\n{{end box}}\n\n{{NorwegianPrimeMinisters}}\n{{Foreigner Minister of Norway}}\n{{Members of the Norwegian Nobel Committee}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Loevland, Joergen}}\n[[Category:1848 births]]\n[[Category:1922 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Evje og Hornnes]]\n[[Category:Norwegian educators]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Storting]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Norway]]\n[[Category:Noregs M\u00e5llag]]\n[[Category:Norwegian Nobel Committee]]\n[[Category:Burials at V\u00e5r Frelsers gravlund]]\n\n{{Norway-politician-1840s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Prime Minister\n| name              = J\u00f8rgen L\u00f8vland\n| image             = J. L\u00f8vland - no-nb digifoto 20160420 00234 NB NS NM 10313 (cropped).jpg\n| order1            = \n| office1           = [[Prime Minister of Norway]]\n| term_start1       = 23 October 1907\n| term_end1         = 19 March 1908\n| monarch1          = [[Haakon VII of Norway|Haakon VII]]\n| governor-general1 = \n| predecessor1      = [[Christian Michelsen]]\n| successor1        = [[Gunnar Knudsen]]\n| office2= [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Norway)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]]\n| primeminister2= [[Christian Michelsen]] <br> Himself \n| term_start2= 7 June 1905 \n| term_end2= 19 March 1908 \n| predecessor2= Position established \n| successor2= [[Wilhelm Christopher Christophersen|Wilhelm Christophersen]] \n| office3= [[Minister of Education and Church Affairs (Norway)|Minister of Education and Church Affairs]]\n| term_start3= 26 October 1915\n| term_end3= 20 June 1920 \n| primeminister3= [[Gunnar Knudsen]]\n| predecessor3= [[Aasulv Olsen Bryggesaa|Aasulv Bryggesaa]]\n| successor3= [[Nils Riddervold Jensen]]\n| office4= [[Minister of Labour and Social Inclusion (Norway)|Minister of Labour]]\n| term_start4= 1 June 1900\n| term_end4= 21 October 1903\n| primeminister4= [[Johannes Steen]] <br> [[Otto Blehr]]\n| predecessor4= [[Hans Hein Theodor Nysom|Hans Nysom]]\n| successor4= [[Albert Hansen]]\n| term_start5= 17 February 1898 \n| term_end5= 28 February 1899 \n| primeminister5= [[Johannes Steen]]\n| predecessor5= [[Fredrik Stang Lund]] \n| successor5= Hans Nysom \n| birth_date        = 3 February 1848\n| birth_place       = [[Evje]], [[Norway]]\n| death_date        =  {{Death date and age|df=yes|1922|8|21|1848|2|3}}\n| death_place       = [[Oslo]], [[Norway]]\n| party             = [[Liberal Party of Norway|Liberal Party]]\n| alma_mater        = [[University of Agder|Kristiansand Teacher Training College]]\n| religion          =  \n| spouse            = \n}}\n'''J\u00f8rgen Gunnarsson L\u00f8vland''' (3 February 1848 &ndash; 21 August 1922) was a [[Norway|Norwegian]] educator and civil servant who served as [[Prime Minister]] of the [[Norwegian Parliament]] (1907-1908).<ref>{{cite web|url=   http://www.dokpro.uio.no/cgi-bin/stad/matr50|title=   J\u00f8rgen L\u00f8vland|publisher=    regjeringen.no   |date=   May 7, 2011  |accessdate= June 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:J\u00f8rgen L\u00f8vland, gravminne p\u00e5 V\u00e5r Frelsers gravlund, Oslo.JPG|thumb|Gravesite of J\u00f8rgen L\u00f8vland, V\u00e5r Frelsers gravlund in Oslo]]\n\n==Background==\nL\u00f8vland was born at Lauvland in  [[Evje]] (''Lauvland i Evje herad'') in [[Aust-Agder]], Norway. He came from a farming family. He graduated from [[Kristiansand Teacher Training College|Christianssands Stifts Seminarium]] teachers\u2019 seminary  in 1865. He worked  as primary school teacher in [[Christianssand]] (1866-1878) and then as headmaster in [[Setesdal]] (1878-1884). From 1884 to 1892 he was also editor of ''Christianssands Stiftsavis''.<ref>{{cite web|url=   https://snl.no/J%25C3%25B8rgen_Gunnarson_L%25C3%25B8vland\n|title=   J\u00f8rgen Gunnarson L\u00f8vland|publisher= Store norske leksikon |author= Magnus A. Mardal |accessdate= June 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nHe represented the Liberal party at the Norwegian Parliament (''Storting'') 1886-1888 and again in 1892-1898.  He was Minister of Labour (1898\u20131899, 1900\u20131902, 1902\u20131903), a member of the Council of State Division in [[Stockholm]] (1899\u20131900), Minister of Foreign Affairs (1905 and 1905\u20131907), Prime Minister and Minister of Foreign Affairs (1907\u20131908), and Minister of Education and Church Affairs (1915\u20131920). In 1905 became the  prime minister in Stockholm. He was chair of the Norwegian government of [[Christian Michelsen]]. In October 1907, L\u00f8vland took over as Norwegian Prime Minister when Michelsen resigned. L\u00f8vland resigned the position in March 1908.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsd.uib.no/polsys/index.cfm?urlname=&lan=&MenuItem=N1_1&ChildItem=&State=collapse&UttakNr=33&person=11942|title = J\u00f8rgen Gunnarson L\u00f8vland|publisher =   Norsk samfunnsvitenskapelig datatjeneste AS |accessdate= June 10, 2016}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.regjeringen.no/en/the-government/previous-governments/governments/during-and-after-the-dissolution-of-the-/ministries-1905---1940/ministries-1905---1940/christian-michelsens-government-1905---1/id507098/   |title= Christian Michelsen's Government \n|publisher =Regjeringen|accessdate= April  1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Norwegian Nobel Committee==\nL\u00f8vland was a member of the [[Norwegian Nobel Committee]] from the foundation in 1897 until his death in 1922. He was the committee\u2019s chairman  (1901\u20131921).\n<ref>{{cite web|url=    http://nobelpeaceprize.org/en_GB/nomination_intro/nomination_committee/|title =    Members of the first Norwegian Nobel Committee |publisher =   Nobel Committee|accessdate= June 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe was married to Mathilde L\u00f8vland (1851\u20131938). Following their deaths, both he and his wife were buried at [[V\u00e5r Frelsers gravlund]] in Oslo.\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Commons category|J\u00f8rgen L\u00f8vland}}\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160701054406/http://www.nppri.org/pdf/Vol1_No3.pdf  The Norwegian Nobel Institute Series] \n{{start box}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Christian Michelsen]]| title=[[Prime Minister of Norway]] | years=1907&ndash;1908| after=[[Gunnar Knudsen]]}}\n{{succession box | before=N/A| title=[[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Norway)|Norwegian Minister of Foreign Affairs]] | years=1905&ndash;1908 | after=[[Wilhelm Christopher Christophersen]]}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Aasulv Olsen Bryggesaa|Aasulv Bryggesaa]]| title=[[Minister of Education and Church Affairs (Norway)|Norwegian Minister of Education and Church Affairs]] | years=1915&ndash;1920 | after=[[Nils Riddervold Jensen]]}}\n{{s-culture}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Marius H\u00e6gstad]]| title=Chairman of [[Noregs M\u00e5llag]] | years=1909&ndash;1912| after=[[Nikolaus Gjelsvik]]}}\n{{end box}}\n\n{{NorwegianPrimeMinisters}}\n{{Foreigner Minister of Norway}}\n{{Members of the Norwegian Nobel Committee}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Loevland, Joergen}}\n[[Category:1848 births]]\n[[Category:1922 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Evje og Hornnes]]\n[[Category:Norwegian educators]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Storting]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Norway]]\n[[Category:Noregs M\u00e5llag]]\n[[Category:Norwegian Nobel Committee]]\n[[Category:Burials at V\u00e5r Frelsers gravlund]]\n\n{{Norway-politician-1840s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's, 1892-1898 \u2192 1892\u20131898", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J%C3%B8rgen_L%C3%B8vland"}
{"title_page": "30,000 Pounds of Bananas", "text_new": "{{short description|Song performed by Harry Chapin}}\n{{Refimprove\n| date = August 2016\n}}\n\n'''\"30,000 Pounds Of Bananas,\"''' sometimes spelled '''\"Thirty Thousand Pounds Of Bananas,\"''' is a [[folk rock]] song by [[Harry Chapin]] from his [[1974 in music|1974]] album, ''[[Verities & Balderdash]].'' The song became more popular in its live extended recording from Chapin's [[1976 in music|1976]] concert album, ''[[Greatest Stories Live]]'' that started the phrase ''\"Harry, it sucks.\"'' The song is based on an actual truck accident that occurred in [[Scranton, Pennsylvania]], in 1965.<ref name=leader>{{cite news|title=It wasn't just about 30,000 pounds of bananas: Real accident 36 years ago in Scranton took the life of a truck driver, injured several other people and became the basis for a popular song|last=Lynott|first=Jerry|date=2001-07-08|url=http://archives.timesleader.com/2001/2001_10/2001_07_08_IT_WASN_T_JUST_ABOUT_30_000_POUNDS_OF_BANANAS_REAL_ACCIDENT_36_Y.html|newspaper=Times Leader|location=Wilkes Barre, PA|access-date=2016-10-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702072537/http://archives.timesleader.com/2001/2001_10/2001_07_08_IT_WASN_T_JUST_ABOUT_30_000_POUNDS_OF_BANANAS_REAL_ACCIDENT_36_Y.html|archive-date=2015-07-02|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://whizzo.blogspot.com/2006/07/harry-chapins-30000-pounds-of-bananas.html |title=Whizzo World Blog: Harry Chapin's 30,000 Pounds of Bananas |publisher=Whizzo.blogspot.com |date=2006-07-17 |accessdate=2010-10-21}}</ref><ref name=\"wnep\">{{Cite news|url=http://wnep.com/2015/03/18/the-banana-truck-crash-50-years-later/|title=The \u2018Banana Truck\u2019 Crash: 50 Years Later|last=Buynovsky|first=Sarah|date=March 18, 2015|work=wnep.com|access-date=2016-06-05|via=}}</ref>\n\n==Incident==\nOn March 18, 1965, a 33-year-old [[truck driver]], Eugene P. Sesky, was on his way to deliver a load of [[Cavendish banana|bananas]] to [[Scranton, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=leader/><ref name=scrtimes>{{cite news|title=1 Killed and 15 Injured in Runaway Accident|last=Carden|first=Terry|date=1965-03-19|df=mdy|url=http://blogs.thetimes-tribune.com/pages/index.php/2015/03/19/tragedy-on-moosic-st/|newspaper=The Scranton Times|access-date=2016-10-28|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150322050210/http://blogs.thetimes-tribune.com/pages/index.php/2015/03/19/tragedy-on-moosic-st/|archivedate=2015-03-22}}</ref><ref name=grit>{{cite web|url=http://gritinthegears.blogspot.com/2007/07/fruit.html |title=Grit in the Gears: Fruit |publisher=Gritinthegears.blogspot.com |date=2007-07-24 |accessdate=2010-10-21}}</ref> Sesky, an employee of Fred Carpentier\u2014operator of a small truck line in Scranton\u2014was returning from the boat piers at [[Newark, New Jersey]], where he had picked up his load. The load was destined for the [[The Great Atlantic & Pacific Tea Company|A&P produce Warehouse]] in South Side<ref name=leader/><ref name=leader/><ref>{{cite news|title=1 Killed and 15 Injured in Runaway Accident|last=Carden|first=Terry|date=1965-03-19|df=mdy|newspaper=The Scranton Times}}</ref>. Sesky was driving a 1950s [[Brockway Motor Company|Brockway]] diesel [[Semi-trailer truck|truck]] tractor with a {{convert|35|ft|m|abbr=on}} [[semi-trailer]] and was headed down [[Pennsylvania Route 307|Rt. 307]] when he lost control. That section of Rt. 307 contains a two-mile descent extending from [[Lake Scranton]] to the bottom of Moosic Street that includes a drop in elevation of more than {{convert|500|ft|m|abbr=on|adj=on}} in less than {{convert|1.5|mi|km|abbr=on|adj=on}}.  Sesky was unable to control the truck's speed down the hill due to a mechanical failure, variously attributed to the truck's brake system<ref name=leader/><ref name=scrtimes/> or its clutch.<ref name=wnep/>  As a result, the truck cruised into Scranton at approximately {{convert|90|mph||abbr=on}}, sideswiping a number of cars before it crashed into a house<ref name=leader/> at the southwest corner of Moosic St and S. Irving Ave ({{Coord|41.4000|N|75.6550|W|display=inline,title}}),<ref name=\"wnep\"/> close to the bottom of the hill.  Witnesses reported that Sesky did everything possible to avoid pedestrians and other motorists,<ref name=wnep/> including climbing out onto the truck's running board to try to warn people,<ref name=leader/> and some have suggested that he may have deliberately flipped the truck over to avoid striking either bystanders or an automotive [[Filling station|service station]]<ref name=songplaces>{{cite web|url=http://www.songplaces.com/30_000_Pounds_Of_Bananas/Moosic_Street_Scranton_Pennsylvania|title=30,000 Pounds Of Bananas by Harry Chapin in Moosic Street, Scranton, Pennsylvania|last=Suwak|first=Jeff|website=Songplaces.com|accessdate=2016-10-28}}</ref> on Moosic Street that could have exploded in flames, causing a greater loss of life. Sesky was thrown from the truck and killed<ref name=leader/> and bananas were spilled and strewn when the rig came to rest; 15 others were injured but only Sesky died. The road was closed for cleanup<ref name=scrtimes/> as Johnson's Towing Company helped out in the recovery. Trucks over 21,000 lbs were required to go down the hill in first, low gear. Trucks over 21,000 lb (10.5 t) are no longer allowed to travel that route (they must use [[Interstate 380 (Pennsylvania)|Interstate 380]] via [[Dunmore, Pennsylvania|Dunmore]]).\n\n==Song==\nThe song portrays a [[fiction]]al account of the incident played in the form of a [[Country music|country song]]. With each verse, the song gets faster to, as Chapin explained in the live recording, \"build up intensity and excitement.\" During the chorus, Chapin sings the phrase \"thirty-thousand pounds\" followed by [[John Wallace (musician)|Big John Wallace]] singing the bass line \"of bananas.\" During concerts, the audience was encouraged to shout this refrain.\n\n===Content===\nA young truck driver is driving \"just after dark\" during his \"second job\" to deliver a load of bananas to Scranton, which is described as a \"[[Coal mining|coal-scarred]] city where children play without despair in back-yard [[slag]] piles,\" the population of which consumes about {{convert|30,000|lb|tonne|abbr=off}} of bananas daily. While approaching Scranton, he passes a sign he \"should have seen\" reading: \"Shift to [[low gear]] or [[Traffic ticket|fifty-dollar fine]], my friend,\" because he is too busy thinking about seeing his wife after his trip. He begins to travel down the \"two-mile drop\" road to the bottom of the hill. Suddenly, the truck begins to go faster down the hill, and the driver tries to apply the [[brake]]s, only to discover that they are not working. He says, \"[[Christ]]!\" who ironically is \"the only Man who could save him now\" as the load of bananas push against the truck causing it to pick up speed. Cruising into Scranton at \"about ninety miles an hour,\" he almost strikes a passing bus. The driver then prays twice to God to make the event all a dream before he \"sideswiped nineteen neat-parked cars / Clipped off thirteen [[Utility pole|telephone poles]] / Hit two houses, bruised eight trees / And [[Blue Cross Blue Shield Association|Blue-Cross]]ed seven people.\" He is killed and [[decapitation|decapitated]] in the accident, and {{convert|400|yd|m|abbr=off}} of the hill is smeared with his load of bananas.<ref name=leader/>\n\nThe song's epilogue tells the story how Chapin first heard of the event aboard a [[Greyhound Lines|Greyhound bus]] coming out of Scranton some months later. An old man sitting next to Chapin implores him to imagine \"30,000 pounds of mashed bananas.\"\n\nMany details in the song correspond closely to the actual incident,<ref name=songplaces/> but others are invented or fictionalized.  In particular, Sesky was not actually decapitated in the accident.<ref name=leader/>\n\n===Alternate endings===\nIn the live performance from the album ''[[Greatest Stories Live]],'' Chapin sings two alternate endings to the song he originally had in mind, explaining to the audience that the rest of the band was less than enthusiastic about them, with his brothers [[Tom Chapin|Tom]] and [[Steve Chapin|Steve]] each offering the summary dismissal, \"Harry, it sucks!\" The first alternate ending uses ''[[Yes! We Have No Bananas]]'' as the punchline of the song.\n\nThe second ending is described by Chapin as a \"country-western\" ending about \"motherhood\", because the song \"already had a truck.\" It deals with a young mother crying while watching her child sleeping. The woman is presumably the truck driver's widow and, because of her sorrow over the accident, \"though she lives in Scranton, Pennsylvania / she never, ever eats bananas.\" During concerts, Chapin divided the audience during this ending, usually turning it into a contest between men and women with regard to singing skill. The second alternate ending has everyone sing \"of Bananas!\" in harmony, swelling to a climax and cutting off.\n\nA third alternate ending surfaced later, in which Chapin would often introduce with a monologue about [[Donny Osmond|Donny]] and [[Marie Osmond]], and the technical definition of the word \"[[Wikt:suck|sucks]]\". The third alternate ending is a parody of a [[Chiquita Brands International|Chiquita banana]] commercial, done in \"[[Jimmy Buffett]] style,\" with the participation of the whole band. The ending is cut short by Big John singing the first verse of \"[[Taxi (song)|Taxi]]\" in the form of an upbeat disco style that concludes with Chapin telling him \"it sucks.\"\n\n''The Bottom Line'' CD features the four endings along with \"Final Concert.\" Other recorded examples of the song with all four endings include performances at [[Knoxville Memorial Stadium]] on March 7, 1979; the Coffee Break Concert broadcast on [[WMMS]] Cleveland on December 5, 1979; and the [[Boston University]] concert on April 1, 1981.\n\n\"Harry, it sucks\" became a popular [[catchphrase]] among Chapin's fans, to the point where [[T-shirt]]s sporting the phrase would be offered at his concerts.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Harry Chapin}}\n\n[[Category:1974 songs]]\n[[Category:Bananas in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Songs about food]]\n[[Category:Songs about truck driving]]\n[[Category:Harry Chapin songs]]\n[[Category:Scranton, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Songs based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Harry Chapin]]\n[[Category:Vehicle wreck ballads]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Paul Leka]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Song performed by Harry Chapin}}\n{{Refimprove\n| date = August 2016\n}}\n\n'''\"30,000 Pounds Of Bananas,\"''' sometimes spelled '''\"Thirty Thousand Pounds Of Bananas,\"''' is a [[folk rock]] song by [[Harry Chapin]] from his [[1974 in music|1974]] album, ''[[Verities & Balderdash]].'' The song became more popular in its live extended recording from Chapin's [[1976 in music|1976]] concert album, ''[[Greatest Stories Live]]'' that started the phrase ''\"Harry, it sucks.\"'' The song is based on an actual truck accident that occurred in [[Scranton, Pennsylvania]], in 1965.<ref name=leader>{{cite news|title=It wasn't just about 30,000 pounds of bananas: Real accident 36 years ago in Scranton took the life of a truck driver, injured several other people and became the basis for a popular song|last=Lynott|first=Jerry|date=2001-07-08|url=http://archives.timesleader.com/2001/2001_10/2001_07_08_IT_WASN_T_JUST_ABOUT_30_000_POUNDS_OF_BANANAS_REAL_ACCIDENT_36_Y.html|newspaper=Times Leader|location=Wilkes Barre, PA|access-date=2016-10-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702072537/http://archives.timesleader.com/2001/2001_10/2001_07_08_IT_WASN_T_JUST_ABOUT_30_000_POUNDS_OF_BANANAS_REAL_ACCIDENT_36_Y.html|archive-date=2015-07-02|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://whizzo.blogspot.com/2006/07/harry-chapins-30000-pounds-of-bananas.html |title=Whizzo World Blog: Harry Chapin's 30,000 Pounds of Bananas |publisher=Whizzo.blogspot.com |date=2006-07-17 |accessdate=2010-10-21}}</ref><ref name=\"wnep\">{{Cite news|url=http://wnep.com/2015/03/18/the-banana-truck-crash-50-years-later/|title=The \u2018Banana Truck\u2019 Crash: 50 Years Later|last=Buynovsky|first=Sarah|date=March 18, 2015|work=wnep.com|access-date=2016-06-05|via=}}</ref>\n\n==Incident==\nOn March 18, 1965, a 33-year-old [[truck driver]], Eugene P. Sesky, was on his way to deliver a load of [[Cavendish banana|bananas]] to [[Scranton, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=leader/><ref name=scrtimes>{{cite news|title=1 Killed and 15 Injured in Runaway Accident|last=Carden|first=Terry|date=1965-03-19|df=mdy|url=http://blogs.thetimes-tribune.com/pages/index.php/2015/03/19/tragedy-on-moosic-st/|newspaper=The Scranton Times|access-date=2016-10-28|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150322050210/http://blogs.thetimes-tribune.com/pages/index.php/2015/03/19/tragedy-on-moosic-st/|archivedate=2015-03-22}}</ref><ref name=grit>{{cite web|url=http://gritinthegears.blogspot.com/2007/07/fruit.html |title=Grit in the Gears: Fruit |publisher=Gritinthegears.blogspot.com |date=2007-07-24 |accessdate=2010-10-21}}</ref> Sesky, an employee of Fred Carpentier\u2014operator of a small truck line in Scranton\u2014was returning from the boat piers at [[Newark, New Jersey]], where he had picked up his load. The load was destined for the [[The Great Atlantic & Pacific Tea Company|A&P produce Warehouse]] in South Side<ref name=leader/><ref name=leader/><ref>{{cite news|title=1 Killed and 15 Injured in Runaway Accident|last=Carden|first=Terry|date=1965-03-19|df=mdy|newspaper=The Scranton Times}}</ref>. Sesky was driving a 1950s [[Brockway Motor Company|Brockway]] diesel [[Semi-trailer truck|truck]] tractor with a {{convert|35|ft|m|abbr=on}} [[semi-trailer]] and was headed down [[Pennsylvania Route 307|Rt. 307]] when he lost control. That section of Rt. 307 contains a two-mile descent extending from [[Lake Scranton]] to the bottom of Moosic Street that includes a drop in elevation of more than {{convert|500|ft|m|abbr=on|adj=on}} in less than {{convert|1.5|mi|km|abbr=on|adj=on}}.  Sesky was unable to control the truck's speed down the hill due to a mechanical failure, variously attributed to the truck's brake system<ref name=leader/><ref name=scrtimes/> or its clutch.<ref name=wnep/>  As a result, the truck cruised into Scranton at approximately {{convert|90|mph||abbr=on}}, sideswiping a number of cars before it crashed into a house<ref name=leader/> at the southwest corner of Moosic St and S. Irving Ave ({{Coord|41.4000|N|75.6550|W|display=inline,title}}),<ref name=\"wnep\"/> close to the bottom of the hill.  Witnesses reported that Sesky did everything possible to avoid pedestrians and other motorists,<ref name=wnep/> including climbing out onto the truck's running board to try to warn people,<ref name=leader/> and some have suggested that he may have deliberately flipped the truck over to avoid striking either bystanders or an automotive [[Filling station|service station]]<ref name=songplaces>{{cite web|url=http://www.songplaces.com/30_000_Pounds_Of_Bananas/Moosic_Street_Scranton_Pennsylvania|title=30,000 Pounds Of Bananas by Harry Chapin in Moosic Street, Scranton, Pennsylvania|last=Suwak|first=Jeff|website=Songplaces.com|accessdate=2016-10-28}}</ref> on Moosic Street that could have exploded in flames, causing a greater loss of life. Sesky was thrown from the truck and killed<ref name=leader/> and bananas were spilled and strewn when the rig came to rest; 15 others were injured but only Sesky died. The road was closed for cleanup<ref name=scrtimes/> as Johnson's Towing Company helped out in the recovery. Trucks over 21,000 lbs were required to go down the hill in first, low gear. Trucks over 21,000 lb (10.5 t) are no longer allowed to travel that route (they must use [[Interstate 380 (Pennsylvania)|Interstate 380]] via [[Dunmore, Pennsylvania|Dunmore]]).\n\n==Song==\nThe song portrays a [[fiction]]al account of the incident played in the form of a [[Country music|country song]]. With each verse, the song gets faster to, as Chapin explained in the live recording, \"build up intensity and excitement.\" During the chorus, Chapin sings the phrase \"thirty-thousand pounds\" followed by [[John Wallace (musician)|Big John Wallace]] singing the bass line \"of bananas.\" During concerts, the audience was encouraged to shout this refrain.\n\n===Content===\nA young truck driver is driving \"just after dark\" during his \"second job\" to deliver a load of bananas to Scranton, which is described as a \"[[Coal mining|coal-scarred]] city where children play without despair in back-yard [[slag]] piles,\" the population of which consumes about {{convert|30,000|lb|tonne|abbr=off}} of bananas daily. While approaching Scranton, he passes a sign he \"should have seen\" reading: \"Shift to [[low gear]] or [[Traffic ticket|fifty-dollar fine]], my friend,\" because he is too busy thinking about seeing his wife after his trip. He begins to travel down the \"two-mile drop\" road to the bottom of the hill. Suddenly, the truck begins to go faster down the hill, and the driver tries to apply the [[brake]]s, only to discover that they are not working. He says, \"[[Christ]]!\" who ironically is \"the only Man who could save him now\" as the load of bananas push against the truck causing it to pick up speed. Cruising into Scranton at \"about ninety miles an hour,\" he almost strikes a passing bus. The driver then prays twice to God to make the event all a dream before he \"sideswiped nineteen neat-parked cars / Clipped off thirteen [[Utility pole|telephone poles]] / Hit two houses, bruised eight trees / And [[Blue Cross Blue Shield Association|Blue-Cross]]ed seven people.\" He is killed and [[decapitation|decapitated]] in the accident, and {{convert|400|yd|m|abbr=off}} of the hill is smeared with his load of bananas.<ref name=leader/>\n\nThe song's epilogue tells the story how Chapin first heard of the event aboard a [[Greyhound Lines|Greyhound bus]] coming out of Scranton some months later. An old man sitting next to Chapin implores him to imagine \"30,000 pounds of mashed bananas.\"\n\nMany details in the song correspond closely to the actual incident,<ref name=songplaces/> but others are invented or fictionalized.  In particular, Sesky was not actually decapitated in the accident.<ref name=leader/>\n\n===Alternate endings===\nIn the live performance from the album ''[[Greatest Stories Live]],'' Chapin sings two alternate endings to the song he originally had in mind, explaining to the audience that the rest of the band was less than enthusiastic about them, with his brothers [[Tom Chapin|Tom]] and [[Steve Chapin|Steve]] each offering the summary dismissal, \"Harry, it sucks!\" The first alternate ending uses ''[[Yes! We Have No Bananas]]'' as the punchline of the song.\n\nThe second ending is described by Chapin as a \"country-western\" ending about \"motherhood\", because the song \"already had a truck.\" It deals with a young mother crying while watching her child sleeping. The woman is presumably the truck driver's widow and, because of her sorrow over the accident, \"though she lives in Scranton, Pennsylvania / she never, ever eats bananas.\" During concerts, Chapin divided the audience during this ending, usually turning it into a contest between men and women with regard to singing skill. The second alternate ending has everyone sing \"of Bananas!\" in harmony, swelling to a climax and cutting off.\n\nA third alternate ending surfaced later, in which Chapin would often introduce with a monologue about [[Donny Osmond|Donny]] and [[Marie Osmond]], and the technical definition of the word \"[[Wikt:suck|sucks]]\". The third alternate ending is a parody of a [[Chiquita Brands International|Chiquita banana]] commercial, done in \"[[Jimmy Buffett]] style,\" with the participation of the whole band. The ending is cut short by Big John singing the first verse of \"[[Taxi (song)|Taxi]]\" in the form of an upbeat disco style that concludes with Chapin telling him \"it sucks.\"\n\n''The Bottom Line'' CD features the four endings along with \"Final Concert.\" Other recorded examples of the song with all four endings include performances at [[Knoxville Memorial Stadium]] on March 7, 1979; the Coffee Break Concert broadcast on [[WMMS]] Cleveland on December 5, 1979; and the [[Boston University]] concert on April 1, 1981.\n\n\"Harry, it sucks\" became a popular [[catchphrase]] among Chapin's fans, to the point where [[T-shirt]]s sporting the phrase would be offered at his concerts.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Harry Chapin}}\n\n[[Category:1974 songs]]\n[[Category:Bananas in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Songs about food]]\n[[Category:Songs about truck driving]]\n[[Category:Harry Chapin songs]]\n[[Category:Scranton, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Songs based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Harry Chapin]]\n[[Category:Vehicle wreck ballads]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Paul Leka]]\n", "name_user": "Mdaniels5757", "label": "safe", "comment": "update url status", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/30,000_Pounds_of_Bananas"}
